<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Prime Minister Pays 1st Official Visit to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Canadian Prime
Minister Jean Chretien and U.S. President Bill Clinton today said
that their countries should further develop relations though they
are already very good.
</P>
<P>
In a welcoming ceremony at the White House, Clinton said
Chretien's visit was an occasion on which to "celebrate one of
history's most remarkable partnerships."
</P>
<P>
Chretien, on his first official visit to Washington as prime
minister, agreed that relations between the U.S. and Canada "are
healthy and strong, perhaps more than they have ever been."
</P>
<P>
Clinton, still on crutches due to his right leg injury, said
that the U.S.-Canadian relations "have never been closer or more
constructive."
</P>
<P>
"As we stand on the threshold of a new millennium, let us raise
our beacon high," Clinton stated, saying U.S.-Canadian summits are
"a time to set the beacon jointly."
</P>
<P>
In his remarks, Chretien said, "No relationship can grow or
prosper if it stands still, particularly at a time of rapid
change."
</P>
<P>
"As we move into the 21st century, we must continue to rise to
new challenges and to find more innovative ways of advancing
cooperation, of sharing ideas, and of managing our relations,"
stressed Chretien.
</P>
<P>
According to Clinton, 250,000 people and nearly 1 billion
dollars in trade "cross our border every day." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
