<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Prime Minister Pays 1st State Visit to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Canadian Prime
Minister Jean Chretien and U.S. President Bill Clinton today said
that their countries should further develop relations though they
are already very good.
</P>
<P>
In a welcome ceremony at the White House, Clinton said
Chretien's visit was an occasion on which to "celebrate one of
history's most remarkable partnerships."
</P>
<P>
Chretien arrived here Monday on his first state visit to
Washington as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He agreed that relations between the U.S. and Canada "are
healthy and strong, perhaps more than they have ever been."
</P>
<P>
Clinton, still on crutches due to his right leg injury, said
that the U.S.-Canadian relations "have never been closer or more
constructive."
</P>
<P>
"As we stand on the threshold of a new millennium, let us raise
our beacon high," Clinton stated, saying the U.S.-Canadian summit
is "a time to set the beacon jointly."
</P>
<P>
In his remarks, Chretien said, "No relationship can grow or
prosper if it stands still, particularly at a time of rapid
change."
</P>
<P>
"As we move into the 21st century, we must continue to rise to
new challenges and to find more innovative ways of advancing
cooperation, of sharing ideas, and of managing our relations,"
stressed Chretien.
</P>
<P>
Canada has sharply criticized the U.S. policy towards Cuba,
stressing that the U.S. Helms-Burton law which strengthens the
trade and economic embargo against Cuba is a violation of
international norms.
</P>
<P>
The law, which was enacted last year, punishes those foreign
firms which trade with the Cubans.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today, White House spokesman Michael
McCurry admitted that the two sides have "some political
differences with respect to Helms-Burton."
</P>
<P>
According to Clinton, 250,000 people and nearly 1 billion U.S.
dollars in trade cross the Canadian-U.S. border each day.
</P>
<P>
The value of two-way merchandise trade between the two has
increased 45 percent since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
