<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Government troops in Zaire's second largest city surrendered
to rebels without a fight and thousands of citizens turned to hail
the rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
-- A significant majority of the American public believe that
fundamental changes are needed in the financing system for the
U.S. election campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton tried without success to rescue
the Middle East peace process during tense talks with Israel Prime
minister Benjamin Netanyahu on Monday.
</P>
<P>
-- The tumultuous revolt in Vlore, Albania, has settled into an
uneasy stalemate that leaves the little corner of the Balkans
almost lawless.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Profit prospects for Ford and GM are on the rise this year
resulting from plans to boost vehicle production and successful
cost cutting.
</P>
<P>
-- A Pulitzer Prize was awarded to Wall Street Journal reporters
for chronicling the development and effects of new AIDS therapies.
</P>
</TEXT>
