<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Claims Responsibility for Grand National Bomb Alerts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Army (IRA) has
claimed responsibility for the two bomb alerts that caused massive
emergency evacuation and brought the postponement of the
traditional Grand National horse-racing event.
</P>
<P>
The claim was made today by an unnamed caller using a
recognized IRA code word to Ireland's semi-state RTE broadcasting
network, according to reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
An RTE spokesman quoted the caller as saying that such actions
would not be needed if the British government adopted a
constructive attitude to the Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The IRA were responsible for the disruption of the Grand
National in England on Saturday. We remind John Major that had he
given as much importance to the negotiating of an end to the
conflict in Northern Ireland over the past few years as he
attaches to the disruption of a single sporting event, a lasting
peace settlement would have been closer," the caller said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The British government has repeatedly made it clear that Sinn
Fein, the political wing of the IRA, would not be admitted into
the all-party peace talks until the IRA guerillas call a permanent
cease-fire and hand over all its arms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
