<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Formally Announces Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides today officially announced a cabinet reshuffle, the first
since he formed his government after he was elected to a five-year
term in February 1993.
</P>
<P>
A written statement, issued by the president this afternoon,
listed the names of the new members of the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Former government spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides replaced
Alecos P. Michaelides as minister of foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
Nicos Koshis is the new minister of justice and public order,
taking over the post from Alecos Evangelou.
</P>
<P>
Minister of education and culture is now Georghios
Hadjinicolaou, who replaces Claire Angelidou.
</P>
<P>
Christos Solomis takes over from Manolis Christofides as
health minister.
</P>
<P>
Leontios Ierodiaconou is now minister of communications and
works, replacing Adamos Adamides.
</P>
<P>
Manolis Christofides, former health minister, takes over
Cassoulides' job as government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The new ministers will give their prescribed affirmation of
office before the president on Wednesday morning, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Clerides' former government is made up of eleven ministers. Six
ministers came from the ruling rightwing Democratic Rally party
and five were from its government partner, the center-right
Democratic Party led by former Cypriot President Spyros Kyprianou.
</P>
<P>
Five ministers replaced in the reshuffle came from the
ruling Democratic Rally party.
</P>
<P>
Former government spokesman, now Foreign Minister Yiannakis
Cassoulides described the government reshuffle this morning as
"a political act" stemming from the president's constitutional
right, but he declined to go into details.
</P>
<P>
The next presidential elections in Cyprus will take place
in February 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
