<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Treasury Secretary Eases Vietnam Debt Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- United States Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin left Ho Chi Minh City today, ending his three-day
visit to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
It was the first visit by a U.S. treasury secretary to Vietnam
since the Vietnam war ended in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Rubin held talks with his Vietnamese counterpart in Hanoi
Monday, and signed an accord after the talks to reschedule a
debt of 145 million U.S. dollars accumulated by the former Saigon
regime during the war.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, Vietnam will pay 8.5 million U.S. dollars
within 30 days while the rest of the debt will be rescheduled by
stages within the next 22 years.
</P>
<P>
Rubin described the signing as "an important step towards
normalization between the two countries, and the entry by Vietnam
into the international financial community."
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Vice Foreign Minister for American Affairs Nguyen
Dinh Bin said the signing was a positive indication of the two
countries' determination to "end the past and open the future."
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Rubin met separately with Secretary General
of the Vietnamese Communist Party Do Muoi today, and Prime
Minister Vo Van Kiet Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese leaders told Rubin there were positive signs
since normalization between the two countries, especially in the
economic fields.
</P>
<P>
But they argued that relations between the two countries had
not been fully normalized, and Vietnam was not responsible for the
slow progress the two had made in normalizing their economic
relationship.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam looked to enhance the economic and trade cooperation
with the United States, they stressed.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade volume hit 935 million U.S. dollars in
1996, double that of the previous year. The United States has
invested 1.2 billion U.S. dollars in Vietnam, and was its eighth
biggest foreign investor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
