<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshop on Culture, Gender and Development Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A four-day sub-regional
workshop on culture, gender and development for eastern and
southern African English speaking countries opened here today
with a view to finding ways of integrating socio-cultural factors
with development efforts.
</P>
<P>
In an opening speech, Woldemichael Chemu, Minister of
Information and Culture of Ethiopia, said the workshop has given
great attention to culture, gender and development which are very
crucial issues for African situation at this particular time.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the participants that "this is because, the
diversity of traditions and cultures, developing economic
situation and the new gender issues prevailing in Africa calls
for an immediate and concrete actions".
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the minister continued, "the invasion of the
'modern' colonial culture against the development of the
indigenous one, again, needs for an urgent means of
reconciliation in this continent."
</P>
<P>
He hoped the workshop "would seriously examine the critical
linkages between culture, gender and development, in light of the
present situation existing in Africa in general and in sub-region
in particular".
</P>
<P>
The workshop is being organized by the Ethiopian Ministry of
Information and Culture and the African itinerant college for
culture and development based in Dakar.
</P>
<P>
Over 80 delegates from Kenya, Eritrea, Tanzania, Zambia,
Zimbabwe, Senegal and Ethiopia as well as representatives from
the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) are
attending the workshop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Sees no Decline of Extremist Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Neo-Nazi violence showed almost no
decline last year in Germany, with the former east German area
experiencing the worst violence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leftists intensified attacks against nuclear waste
transport, said a government report released today.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the number of active right wing extremists in Germany
fell slightly, to 45,300 from 46,100 in the previous year. They
were responsible for 507 violent attacks causing injury, two less
than in 1995, as well as for 33 arsons, compared with 45 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The overall number of "rightist" crimes rose to 8,730, an
increase of 834 cases. Many of the cases resulted in convictions
for distributing neo-Nazi propaganda, said the annual report on
extremism in Germany, presented by the Office for the Protection
of the Constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Woos Local, Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina today made a clarion call to investors and entrepreneurs
from home and abroad to come forward with their capital and
technology.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the expansion project of Dhaka Export Processing
Zone (EPZ), the prime minister assured the investors of all
possible cooperation and assistance to reduce production cost and
fetch maximum profits.
</P>
<P>
"The investors can utilize the world's most inexpensive labor
force available in Bangladesh and the highly competitive package
of fiscal and nonfiscal incentives and facilities, being provided
by my government," Hasina claimed.
</P>
<P>
The expansion project of Dhaka EPZ, situated on 214 acres,
would have 260 industrial plots each having 2,000 square meters.
The government has taken up the project on July 25, last year
while physical possession of the land was taken on January 19 this
year.
</P>
<P>
In less than two months 50 percent of the construction work on
the physical infrastructure was completed and the project is
expected to be completed in the next two years, said official
sources, adding that this would be a record in implementing such a
project in this country in such a short time.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister told the gathering that the industrial
policy of her government was aimed at accelerating the growth of
export oriented industries through an appropriately designed
export strategy, which is expected to reduce the country's huge
trade imbalance.
</P>
<P>
The government has undertaken massive programs worldwide to
achieve this objective, said Hasina, adding that 1997 has been
declared as the year of investment in Bangladesh, one of the most
undeveloped countries in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Sees no Decline of Extremist Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Neo-Nazi violence showed almost no
decline last year in Germany, with the former east German area
experiencing the worst violence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leftists intensified attacks against nuclear waste
transport, said a government report released today.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the number of active right wing extremists in Germany
fell slightly, to 45,300 from 46,100 in the previous year. They
were responsible for 507 violent attacks causing injury, two less
than in 1995, as well as for 33 arsons, compared with 45 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The overall number of "rightist" crimes rose to 8,730, an
increase of 834 cases. Many of the cases resulted in convictions
for distributing neo-Nazi propaganda, said the annual report on
extremism in Germany, presented by the Office for the Protection
of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Anti-Semitic crimes declined by 27 percent from 1995, to 846,
while violent cases climbed to 29 last year from 27 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The only death caused by neo-Nazis in 1996, which was also the
only such death reported in the past three years, occurred in the
eastern German state of Brandenburg, where neo-Nazi violence was
most frequent.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that eastern Germany suffered the highest per
capita rates of neo-Nazi violence last year, with Brandenburg
topping the list with 3.35 attacks per 100,000 inhabitants,
followed by Mecklenburg-West Pomerania, with 2.95.
</P>
<P>
The report voiced concern over the increasing number of male
youths involved in violent rightest attacks, noting that over 66
percent of the 751 people convicted of such crimes in 1996 were
aged 16 to 20, and only four percent were female.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing extremists totalled 32,500 last year, and were
held by the report to be responsible for 932 attacks, down from
965 in 1995. They included 30 violent cases resulting in injury,
compared with 35 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The report said leftists carried out 154 attacks on transport
systems last year, up from 114 in 1995, leading to huge repair
bills. It noted that one million marks (588,000 U.S. dollars) was
spent only to replace a mast carrying overhead rail power lines
which was cut down last May near Hanover.
</P>
<P>
In particular, leftists intensified assaults on railways used
for shipping nuclear waste to a storage depot in Lower Saxony
state, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that Berlin, with its traditional left-wing
background, recorded the highest level of leftist violence last
year, with 5.07 such crimes per 100,000 inhabitants, up sharply
from 2.56 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Of all the 16 German states, Bavaria in western Germany
registered the lowest rate of either violent right or left-wing
attacks, with 0.25 and 0.08 attacks respectively for each 100,
000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
