<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Countries not Qualified to Judge Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Developed countries are not
qualified to pass judgement on human rights conditions in
developing countries, Wu Jianmin, Head of the Chinese delegation
to the United Nations Commission on Human Rights, said here today.
</P>
<P>
The human rights records of the developed countries are far
from perfect, Wu said. He was speaking at the 53rd session of the
commission on Item 10 -- violation of human rights and fundamental
freedoms in any part of the world.
</P>
<P>
The majority of these developed countries do not have decent
human rights records in history, he added.
</P>
<P>
During the industrialization process, they had for a long time
violated the human rights of other countries, systematically and
on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
The Western countries engaged in the trade of black slaves for
about four centuries. Its devastating consequences had not been
eradicated yet. Africa remained the poorest continent of the world.
</P>
<P>
The Western countries have the unshirkable responsibility for
the human rights problems the world faces today, he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Commission on Human Rights should encourage
cooperation and reject confrontation, Wu said, pointing out that
the Commission on Human Rights is the principle body for the
consideration of human rights issues in the UN system.
</P>
<P>
Confrontation intensifies mutual hostility and leads the
commission astray. Past experience has proved that confrontation
is a blind alley and holds no future for the commission, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
The commission should encourage democracy and oppose the
practice of a few developed countries imposing on others. Many
developed countries have the propensity to make prescriptions for
developing countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
The commission should abide by the principle of equality and
mutual respect and oppose the practice of the big oppressing the
small, the strong bullying the weak. Sovereign equality was the
primary principle laid down in the UN Charter as the cornerstone
of the United Nations, Wu added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
