<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Calls For Education Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- During a tour of eastern Shandong
Province today, Vice-premier Li Lanqing called for a shift in
China's traditional exam-oriented educational system to one that
places more emphasis on quality.
</P>
<P>
Chinese schools should seek to produce students of high
quality, he said, rather than students who are good at taking
examinations and poor in ability.
</P>
<P>
"This is an issue of more than just educational skills," he
noted during a visit to Zhaoyuan city, which is renowned for its
quality-oriented education. "It's an issue of the guiding policy
of education, and an issue that has a significant bearing on the
future of the country."
</P>
<P>
We should abandon the past practice of regarding academic level
as the only yardstick, and establish a thorough scientific
evaluation system to judge the performance of both teachers and
students, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier also called for an improvement in the quality
of teaching staff and a revision of textbooks that is in line with
educational reforms.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that illegal tuition fees or charging
excessive fees should be halted and that those who impose them
should be severely penalized.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged that reforms in China's system of higher
education will be increased for more rational and better use of
its educational resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
