<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK New Car Sales Down in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- New car sales in Britain in March
stand at 179,863 units, 0.23 percent lower than last March,
figures published today by the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders (SMMT) show.
</P>
<P>
However, in the first quarter of this year, sales increased by
3.5 percent to 549,534 from 531,049 over the same period in 1996,
with the bulk of the growth in January.
</P>
<P>
The SMMT expressed concern at last month's sales and pointed
out that the slowdown conflicted with surveys showing retail
spending picking up.
</P>
<P>
One possibility was that the buyers were put off by election
uncertainty and the likelihood of higher interest rates whichever
party won next month's election.
</P>
<P>
But the SMMT believed that the industry remained on course to
break through the two million level this year.
</P>
<P>
Private buyers accounted for 43 percent of sales in March and
the first quarter as a whole, the same as last year.
</P>
<P>
The market share of imported cars continued to surge last
month to 65.29 percent, up from 61 percent in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter of this year, imports accounted for 65.4
percent of the market, up from 61.4 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The SMMT said market shares of traditional market leaders,
such as Ford, Vauxhall and the Rover group, all slid in March, to
16.9 percent (from 17.8 percent in the previous March), 13.5
percent (from 15.4 percent) and 10.9 percent (from 12 percent)
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The main beneficiaries were imported European brands, with
Fiat's share jumping to 4.6 percent from 3.6 percent, its best
March since the 1970s, and Citroen's to 5.4 percent from 3.3
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
