<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marco Polo's Family Still Has Feelings for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Marco Polo could hardly have
imagined, more than 700 years ago, when he took Chinese noodles
and meat pies back to Italy, that Italian pizza and spaghetti
would be as they now are in the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Nor could he imagine that his descendants would have the same
feelings for China that he did, or that a relative 30 generations
later, Siro Polo, would be an expert on Chinese history, culture
and economy.
</P>
<P>
Siro is making his 36th visit to China and is scheduled to
speak on China's economic development at the 32nd World Congress
of the International Chamber of Commerce (ICC) scheduled to open
in Shanghai Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Recalling his first visit to China, as a guest of Chairman Mao
Zedong and Premier Zhou Enlai in 1961, Siro told Xinhua that his
family has deep feelings for China and that he still wears a small
gold tag on his wrist watch that was presented by Zhou.
</P>
<P>
On its front are engraved the Chinese characters "double
happiness" and on the back "love".
</P>
<P>
Since his meeting with Mao and Zhou, Siro has visited China a
number of times, and says that he has seen China's reforms,
opening up and economic development, and over the past several
years has become a kind of envoy from Italy to China.
</P>
<P>
When he first visited China, he attended the inauguration of a
museum commemorating Marco Polo and took part in talks on mutual
recognition between Italy and China.
</P>
<P>
In 1971, he participated in activities aimed at restoring
China's legitimate status in the United Nations, resulting in the
Italian government's vote in October favoring restoration.
</P>
<P>
Three years after he was appointed as the European Union's
special envoy to China in 1985, he sponsored the Euro-China
Marketing Network, and in 1989 set up the Center for China and
Asian Studies.
</P>
<P>
He also produced two important works: "Marketing in China" and
"Joint Ventures in China," both of them on Chinese economic
development.
</P>
<P>
As an expert on China, he also tried to look out for China's
interests in the international arena. At an international
conference last year in Italy, he cited facts and data in praise
of China's great achievements in the reform and opening up drive,
and refuted some attacks on China's opening-up policy and
investment environment.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that the Chinese people's wisdom and China's
rich natural resources, as well as the Chinese leaders' policy,
will ensure the continuous development of China's economy.
</P>
<P>
China is in a crucial position in the internationalization of
the world economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that now, in his 60s, he will continue to make an
effort for cultural, political and economic exchanges between
Europe and China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
