<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM: Israel Hopes for Cooperation Atmosphere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy said here today that Israel hopes to find a cooperation
and negotiation atmosphere on the Middle East Peace Process in
the following days.
</P>
<P>
Levy, also deputy prime minister, made the remarks at the
Ankara Esenboga Airport upon his arrival for a two-day official
visit to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said that agreements on Middle East peace process should be
implemented and the commitments should be fulfilled,
adding: "Israel chose peace with its own will."
</P>
<P>
"All the sides concerned should extend effort to speed up
peace", Levy added.
</P>
<P>
On the bilateral relations between Turkey and Israel, Levy
said that positive developments have been recorded in
Turkish-Israeli ties in the recent years.
</P>
<P>
He said that he brought friendship messages from Israeli
President Ezer Weizman and Israeli Premier Binyamin Nethanyahu to
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is a potential between Ankara and Tel
Aviv which could be used in all fields, adding that the
agreements signed between the two countries did not have
objectives directed toward a third country.
</P>
<P>
There is a 500-million-dollar annual trade volume between
Turkey and Israel and the two countries are determined to
double this in the following years with the implementation of
the free trade agreement signed by Ankara and Tel Aviv last
December.
</P>
<P>
A military training agreement signed by Turkey and Israel
in February 1996 generated fear in Middle East countries that
Turkey was aligning itself with the Jewish state against Syria
and other Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry Spokesman Omer Akbel said Monday
that during Levy's visit, Turkey and Israel were expected to
sign a memorandum of understanding on land transportation, which
is said to serve as the basis of an agreement on
transportation cooperation in the future.
</P>
<P>
Demirel received Levy this evening, but no statement was
announced, according to Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli foreign minister will meet Erbakan and his
Turkish counterpart Tansu Ciller tonight and will proceed to
Istanbul Wednesday after concluding his contacts in Ankara.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
