<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Palestinians Killed in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 8 (Xinhua) -- One Palestinian resident of
Hebron was shot dead by two Jewish settlers this morning, and
two others were killed during clashes with Israeli soldiers
following the shooting incident.
</P>
<P>
The two Jewish settlers, students of the Shavei Hebron Yeshiva,
claimed the Palestinians threw stones and a tear gas canister at
them before they opened fire, killing one Palestinian and
critically wounding two others.
</P>
<P>
However, Palestinian witnesses said that the settlers shot the
man with no reasons, and denied that Qassem Arafeh, 24, who was
killed, had tear gas canisters.
</P>
<P>
The shooting sparked additional clashes between Palestinian
protesters and Israeli soldiers, which led to the death of two
other Palestinians, who was shot by Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
The two Jewish settlers were placed under arrest and quickly
taken out of the area by Israeli troops. Israeli police are
questioning them in order to clarify the circumstances surrounding
the incident.
</P>
<P>
There are also reports of a fourth Palestinian having been
killed but they have not been confirmed by Israeli sources at this
time.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) officials have said over 100
Palestinians injured in the clashes, while Israeli sources have
said several Israeli soldiers were lightly injured by stones and
other objects.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Jibril Rajoub, Chief of the
Palestinian Preventive Security, refused to speak with any
senior Israelis officers during the time of the clashes, which
lasted for several hours.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli army general Uzi Dayan said that the
cooperation between Israeli and Palestinian forces is good,
especially in dealing with rioters at the periphery between
Israel and PNA-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army has imposed a curfew on the area of Hebron
under Israeli control, and military and police reinforcements
fanned out in the area in an attempt to calm the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
