<HEADLINE> Conference on Future Somalia Concluded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The conference by the factions
opposing south Mogadishu faction leader, Hussein Mohamed Aidid,
in Lafweyn hotel of north Mogadishu has been concluded today
after five days of serious debates over Somalia's fate in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
General Adan Abdullahi Nur Gabyow, the current chairman of the
National Salvation Council established in Sodare of Ethiopia has
addressed the conclusion speech.
</P>
<P>
The conference which has its toughest point on how the future
parliament members would be formed for Somalia has concluded with
the proposal of a 151 parliamentarians for the future Somali
government. However, the conference has not yet settled on how
they will be chosen either through regional or tribal lines.
</P>
<P>
The congress has also resolved on the convening of another
meeting by the Sodare group in Mogadishu on May 10 this year
before the other meeting in Bosasso scheduled to take place on
June 10. According to Mr Mohamed Moallim, one of information
secretaries of the conference, the meeting in Mogadishu next
month will solve the minor disputes and prepare for a better
understanding within the factions prior to the Bosasso meeting.
</P>
<P>
The five days long meeting was attended by Somali guests from
Canada and America. The closure ceremony was also attended by
hundreds of guests from the women groups and muslim scholars.
</P>
<P>
The general Adan Abdullahi Gabyow, the chairman of the
congress, has thanked all the people who offered their moral and
material support to the meeting. He also thanked the regional and
international organizations, the neighboring countries and the
Arab League for their support to facilitation in ending Somalia's
crises.
</P>
<P>
The leading figures of Habar Gidir such as Osman Hassan Ali
Atto and colonel Abdullahi Yussuf Ahmed of the Majerten clan from
Bosasso who were Banned to attend the meeting did not show up
during the five days meeting. Political analysts in the capital
suspect that there are new political differences between Ali
Mahdi Mohamed on one side and Osman Ali Atto and colonel
Abdullahi Yussuf on the other. The analysts also predict that the
Bosasso meeting is less likely to take place since Mr Ali Mahdi
is also likely to take his revenge and not attend the Bosasso
meeting as they did on this one in Mogadishu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
