<HEADLINE> Africa Seeks More Benefits From Oil: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 8 (Xinhua) -- African countries and institutions
are not benefiting from the foreign-dominated oil trade industry
despite the existence of opportunities which could see the
continent making significant financial gains and savings from
this energy sector.
</P>
<P>
Instead, some overseas countries were using the continent's
resources to make a profit out of Africa, a co-ordinator of the
forthcoming African oil trade conference, Clive Mutiso told
reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
The conference opens in Harare on Monday and over 200
delegates from across the world representing decision makers and
customers are expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference is expected to provide details for the
first time of the infrastructure and financial needs created by
national energy strategies.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to give Africa and its institutions a bigger
share in the profits of the African oil trade," said Mutiso.
</P>
<P>
He said African countries should be able to attract local
investors in the form of reinsurance companies and other
indigenous concerns, departing from relying on the government,
parastatals and multi-nationals.
</P>
<P>
He added the continent also needed to invest in infrastructure
to exploit different kinds of fuel such as liquid petroleum gas.
Eenditem

=04081801

=04081808
NNNN
02:06 02:06 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
