<HEADLINE> Southern African Peacekeeping Exercise Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Commanders of the southern African
peacekeeping training exercise which started on 4th today
completed a gruelling 36-hour training session in U.N.
peacekeeping doctrines, command procedures and strategies.
</P>
<P>
Battalion commander brigadier Subusiso Moyo of the Zimbabwe
National Army (ZNA) said today the session, held at the Zimbabwe
Staff College in Harare, was designed to equip commanders with
command and control procedures for multi-national operations.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we are as good and ready for any peacekeeping
mission."
</P>
<P>
The peacekeeping exercise, jointly sponsored by the British
military advisory training team and the ZNA at a cost of over
400,000 U.S. dollars, is in three phases coded -- exercises blue
jesa, tsuro and ijuba.
</P>
<P>
Countries participating in the exercise, which will be wrapped
up on April 20, are South Africa, Tanzania, Malawi, Lesotho,
Swaziland, Namibia, Mozambique and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The joint exercise, Africa's first, will also see the training
of troops in drills and mock peacekeeping operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
