<HEADLINE> Camerounian Premier Attends UDEAC Summit in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Camerounian Premier Peter Mafany
Musongue left Yaounde today for Congolese capital Brazzaville to
attend the 32nd summit of heads of state of the Economic and
Customs Union of Central Africa (UDEAC), local radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The summit which opened today will lay the ground for the
creation of the Central African Economic and Monetary Community.
</P>
<P>
The creation of the community coincides with brighter economic
perspectives in UDEAC member nations, particularly, the global
economic growth rate of 4.4 percent in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government will be working with
procedural document prepared by the ministerial committee of the
bank of central African states which met earlier in Brazzaville
under the chairmenship of Cameroun's Budget Minister Roger
Melingui.
</P>
<P>
The summit is scheduledrly to end on April 10.
</P>
<P>
The UDEAC was created in December of 1964 while leaders from
Congo, Gabon, Cameroun, Chad and Central Africa gathered in
Brazzaville to sign an agreement to form the UDEAC aimed at
promoting the local economic cooperation and pave the way for the
realization of the union's economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Including Equatorial Guinea, the UDEAC now has 6 member
nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
