<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Israel Sign Memorandum of Understanding on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu
Ciller and her Israeli counterpart David Levy signed here this
evening a memorandum of understanding on land transportation,
which is said to serve as the basis of an agreement on broader
transportation cooperation in the future.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Ciller said that on the one
hand, Turkey is continuing to develop its relations with Muslim
countries, on the other, Turkey is expanding its ties with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
This was the third accord signed by Turkey and Israel
following a military training agreement and a free trade agreement
inked last year.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, who is also deputy prime minister, expressed her hope
that Turkey and Israel would further develop their cooperation in
the future.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Levy said that there is a very great potential in
cooperation between Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two countries should find opportunity for
further cooperative development in every field, especially from
the perspective of research and development.
</P>
<P>
"As two democratic countries, we should do what we want, but
never oppose a third country," Levy added.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the memorandum of understanding came shortly
after the Arab League called on its members to cease the
normalization of their relations with Israel and to renew the
economic boycott of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The military training agreement signed by Turkey and Israel
in February 1996 generated fear in Middle East countries that
Turkey was aligning itself with Israel against Syria and other
Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ankara has also requested the Israeli government
to review its policy on the building of new Jewish settlements in
East Jerusalem, which led to renewed clashes and violence in
Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
