<HEADLINE> Congolese President Invites Mobutu, Kabila to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Congolese President Pascal Lissouba
today invited Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko and Zaire's rebel
leader Laurent-Desire Kabila to meet in the Congolese city of
Pointe-Noire to negotiate peace, reported Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at a meeting of the central African customs union
in Brazzaville, Lissouba also congratulated the government of
Zaire for agreeing to negotiate with the rebels through the
mediation of South Africa and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"In the name of the Congolese people..., I support the
initiatives of President Mobutu to find a solution through
dialogue to the Zaire crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
While agreeing to take part in the negotiation scheduled for
this week in South Africa, the Zairian rebels are at the gate of
the country's second largest city Lubumbashi and have vowed to go
up to Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"This is why the Congo offers voluntarily to Marshal Mobutu and
Mr. Kabila its superb and peaceful city of Pointe-Noire to shelter
these delicate but saving negotiations... which, if they want,
will be placed under the auspices of the Organization of African
Unity and the United Nations," said Lissouba.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 soldiers from Western countries are now deployed in
the Congo to prepare for the evacuation of thousands of Westerners
from Zaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
