<HEADLINE> UN Backs Peace Process in Angola: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
today said he himself and the United Nations will continue to
support the peace process in Angola in an all round way.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to parliament speaker Roberto De Almeida, the U.N.
chief said it was an encouraging act that deputies from the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) and
members designated to attend the government of national unity and
reconciliation have arrived in Luanda.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA MPs arrived in the Angolan capital recently at long
last after delaying for three times and the Angolan government
today endorsed the assumption of opposition leader by UNITA
chairman Jonas Savimbi, paving the way for the formation of the
government of national unity and reconciliation on April 11.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary deputies will play a vital role in
reconstructing the war torn country in an atmosphere of peace and
national reconciliation, Annan stressed.
</P>
<P>
He hoped Angolan leaders would devote all efforts to
fulfilling this arduous but lofty work in a bid to realize peace
and national reconciliation in Angola and end the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief addressed parliamentary session in Angola
during his four-day visit last month, and for this he expressed
thanks to speaker Almeida. 
</P>
</TEXT>
