<HEADLINE> Jordanian PM: King Hussein Recovers Quickly After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam
Majali said here today that King Hussein was recovering quickly
after undergoing a surgery in the United States.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the king underwent an operation to remove an
enlarged portion of his prostate gland which caused him some
difficulty in urinating, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The king received congratulations from Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat and Egyptian President Mubarak after the surgery,
the radio quoted Majali as saying this evening upon his return
from Washington.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the U.S., the king met with U.S. President
Bill Clinton and discussed with him means of pushing forward the
Middle East peace process and the efforts to remove the obstacles
in the way of the peace march, said Majali who accompanied the
king during the visit.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein also asked the U.S. to play a more vital role in
the peace process, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hussein underwent the surgery at Mayo Clinic, Rochester,
Minnesota. He has been a regular visitor to the clinic since
August 1992 when he underwent a successful cancer surgery.
</P>
<P>
The king has since returned there for annual checkups and has
been pronounced free of cancer. His last visit there took place on
march 23 when he received a series of routine tests that again
proved that he had no traces of cancer.
</P>
<P>
During the king's current visit to the U.S., he also met some
U.S. government officials and signed an investment agreement with
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
