<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR, Rwanda Discussing Refugee Reception </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- UNHCR and the Rwandan government
are negotiating how to receive Rwandan returnees airlifted home
from Kisangani of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Information from Integrated Regional Information Network for
the Great Lakes (IRIN) said further negotiations are required to
determine if the returnees can be airlifted directly to Kigali in
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
On April 5, the Alliance of Democratic Forces for the
Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL) responded to a U.N. appeal and
agreed to a plan for the airlift of Rwandan refugees through
Kisangani, the third largest city of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Four U.N. agencies and the European Union humanitarian office
issued the appeal on April 4 to all sides in the Zairean conflict
urging them to consider the urgent humanitarian needs of hundreds
of thousands of refugees in the war zone.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program (WFP) told IRIN today that it was
prepared to make three aircraft available to the planned
repatriation effort.
</P>
<P>
Two IL-76 and one c-130 cargo aircraft could be used to
shuttle food from either Uganda or Tanzania to Kisangani and then
return carrying refugees, WFP said, adding that up to 500 people
could be transported in this way every day.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of refugees to be flown out of rebel-held
territory in Zaire's rain forest is likely to be some 600
unaccompanied children, according to UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the health situation of most refugees are
in appalling condition after having wandered through the bush for
the past six months, trying to keep ahead of a rebel advance
which started last October.
</P>
<P>
Some 80,000 Rwandan Hutu refugees are stranded south of
Kisangani along the road and railway line to Ubundu, 150
kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
More refugees appeared to be emerging from the forest to join
those already on the roadside as there are about 300,000 Hutu
refugees still suffering in eastern Zaire three years after the
start of the Rwanda genocide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
