<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shuttle Columbia Lands With One Faulty Generator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Space shuttle Columbia
returned to Earth this afternoon, ending a disappointed science
mission that was lopped from 16 days to four because of a
defective electric generator.
</P>
<P>
Columbia, the oldest of the NASA shuttle fleet, touched down on
the concrete runway of Kennedy Space Center, Florida, at 2:33 p.m.
as scheduled. Its two-week mission was cut short Sunday by
problems with one of the shuttle's three electricity-producing
fuel cells.
</P>
<P>
NASA officials decided to end the mission early after engineers
noted a slight discrepancy in the voltage from one section of a
fuel cell, which could catch fire or explode.
</P>
<P>
NASA safety rules require a shuttle to head for home as soon as
possible in the event of a fuel cell failure to protect the crew
against the possibility of a second malfunction.
</P>
<P>
Working with the two remaining generators, astronauts turned
off lights and worked by flashlight in their Spacelab research
module in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
"It's for sure you can't cram 16 days of work into four days,
but we are doing our best at it," said one astronaut.
</P>
<P>
Only 10 percent to 15 percent of the objectives of the
Microgravity Science Laboratory were completed during the
shortened mission. But the quality of the data scientists did
receive was expected to be excellent.
</P>
<P>
According to NASA's plan, the next shuttle mission will be
Atlantis' docking with Russian Space Station Mir. Atlantis will be
launched on May 15 to bring urgently needed equipment including
oxygen generators to Mir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
