<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's Ruling Party Approves Draft Law for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Movement of Popular
Liberation of Angola (MPLA) today endorsed a draft law on the
special status of UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi "for the sake of the
realization of peace and national reconciliation".
</P>
<P>
The remarks was made by Joao Lourenco, the parliamentary
leader of the ruling MPLA, who revealed that a total of 120
members of the National Assembly voted for the draft law, with
six abstaining.
</P>
<P>
The legislation grants the former rebel chief of the national
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) official
status as opposition leader, paving the way for the creation of a
government of national unity on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lourenco said that the move by the ruling party has indicated
to all the people of Angola and the world as a whole that it did
not impose any condition to the adoption of the legislation so
that final peace can be achieved in Angola.
</P>
<P>
He urged the UNITA to also take such an attitude to fully
implement the 1994 Lusaka Peace Agreement in favor of the highest
interest of the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped that after the government of national unity
and reconciliation takes office, the UNITA will quicken its pace
to complete its tasks stipulated by the Lusaka accord, including
Savimbi's settling down in capital Luanda.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan people should be united immediately to build a
"new, free, democratic and prosperous Angola", he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
