<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cease-fire in War-Torn Zaire to Be Hopefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A cease-fire and inclusive
elections in war-torn Zaire are hopefully in the offing after
warring parties today agreed that the on-going conflict in their
country should be settled peacefully, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Pretoria, South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki said delegations of the Zairean government
and rebel leader Laurent Kabila had already started consulting
principles on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, a major peace broker in the Zairean peace talks
currently held at an undisclosed venue in Pretoria, said the two
sides had had useful discussions on the timing and modalities of
the proposed cease-fire during the past four-day's face-to-face
talks.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki read a statement signed by the two parties in which they
agreed on negotiations to bring about a peace solution to the
conflict in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
"This necessitates a complete cessation of hostilities and
other measures consistent with the United Nations/Organization of
African Unity peace plan," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Both parties also underlined the need for fundamental and
democratic change in Zaire, and agreed on the need for a
transitional process leading to what was called fair elections,
organized and supervised by an independent body.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, leader of the rebel delegation Bizima Karaha
described the past four-day's talks as good, saying more common
points that divergences had emerged.
</P>
<P>
Zairean Foreign Affairs Minister Kamanda wa Kamanda said not
all the country's problems could be solved in one way, adding,
"we are entering a dynamic process and a greater understanding
has come to light." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
