<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Latin America Pledge to Forge Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NOORDWIJK, the Netherlands, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The European
Union and Latin America pledged today to forge closer ties, aiming
at increased trade and planning a first summit next year.
</P>
<P>
"Our relations can and will be better," Foreign Minister Hans
van Mierlo of the Netherlands, the country which holds the EU
presidency, said after a two-day meeting of foreign ministers from
the 15-nation bloc and their counterparts from 12 Latin American
countries in the Dutch town of Noordwijk.
</P>
<P>
Van Mierlo said great progress had been made in strengthening
trade, political and cultural links and talks had developed from
"merely reading out statements to have a lively exchange of
views."
</P>
<P>
EU Officials said a first EU-Latin America summit would
probably be held in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The summit should not be simply a symbol, it should be
achieving substantial results," Van Mierlo said.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, the ministers said the two sides had
common views on many global issues and "considerable progress" had
been achieved within the framework of the political dialogue
between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
Without having referred specifically to the Helms-Burton Act of
the United States, which aims to punish countries doing business
with Cuba, the ministers condemned in their statement "any
unilateral measure having extraterritorial effect to international
law and to established free trade rules."
</P>
<P>
"Sanctions or certifications... both of these are unilateralism
and they are wrong," said Manuel Marin, European commissioner
responsible for the EU's relations with Latin America.
</P>
<P>
He also said that nations which consume narcotic drugs should
take more responsibility for helping stop their production by
encouraging alternative crops.
</P>
<P>
"Responsibility cannot be reduced to the producers... there is
another responsibility to those countries which consume drugs," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In their statement, the ministers also pledged more cooperation
in fighting international crime.
</P>
<P>
With the siege of the Japanese embassy in Peru by the radical
Tupac Amaru group entering its 113th day today, the ministers said
they "condemn all acts of terrorism, in all its forms and
manifestations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
