<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Hopes Russia, NATO Sign Treaty Before End of May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Alain Juppe
said today that France wishes that Russia and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) could sign before the end of May a
treaty which is aimed at reducing Russian opposition to NATO's
eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Juppe made the statement after holding talks this afternoon
with Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni Primakov, who arrived here
today for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He said that France supports NATO's expansion plan, as long as
it does not threaten to create "in the heart of Europe new lines
of fracture."
</P>
<P>
Juppe also said that France will do its best to help Russia
obtain "access to a certain number of international
institutions" within the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Russia and NATO are now negotiating on a treaty on bilateral
relations, in the hope of reaching an agreement before the NATO
Madrid summit to be held on July 8-9, which will decide on the
eastward expansion program of the trans-Atlantic military
alliance.
</P>
<P>
If the two sides reach an agreement, chiefs of state from NATO
member countries and Russia could meet in Paris at the end of May
to sign the treaty, which will establish a mechanism for
consultation and measures of confidence-building between the two
former enemies during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Russia is strongly opposed to NATO's expansion plan which will
take in former members of the Soviet bloc and push the frontier of
the Western military alliance up to the border of Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic are expected to be
absorbed by NATO in the first wave of its expansion in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
