<HEADLINE> Athens: Most Greek Troops to be Deployed in Tirana, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Greece had agreed today to the
Italian proposal concerning the locations of the 700-strong Greek
troops to be stationed in the strife-ridden Albania, a Greek
government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Nikos Athanassakis said that according to Rome's proposal, the
main Greek troops would be stationed in the Albanian capital of
Tirana, with another company in Avlona.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the presence of the Greek force was related
only to security and stability in the region as well as with the
humanitarian aid which would be sent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos said
today that the Greek force would be consist of both regular
soldiers and volunteers with a five year tour of duty.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the multinational force was expected to
be ready to depart at the beginning of next week.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations approved the formation of a 5,000-strong
multinational security force, half of which will be deployed and
half held in reserve, to protect humanitarian relief operations in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
Troops from Italy, France, Spain, Hungary, Romania and Turkey
are also expected to participate in the U.N.-mandated operation
which will last for three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
