<HEADLINE> Turkish PM: Israel Must Abandon New Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Islamist Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan said this evening that Israel must abandon its
project of building a new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan made the remarks while meeting with Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy, who arrived here this afternoon for a
two-day official visit to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said that Israel must implement the relevant
U.N. resolutions and withdraw immediately from the occupied Arab
lands accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining Middle East peace is very important not only for
the region, but also for the whole world, Erbakan said, adding
that in order to restore peace, some basic principles must be
observed.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who is also deputy prime minister, said that Israel has
selected the way of peace on its own will.
</P>
<P>
"Peace is a phenomenon to serve the whole region. Israel
implements the Oslo agreement," Levy said. "Direct talks must be
realized, terrorism must be eradicated."
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Levy conveyed an invitation from Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu to Erbakan to pay an official visit to
Israel at a proper time.
</P>
<P>
During the signing ceremony of a memorandum of understanding on
land transportation between Turkey and Israel this evening,
Turkish deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller
said that Turkey is very closely following the deteriorating
relations between Israel and neighboring countries, especially
between Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat and
Netanyahu in the framework of the Peace Process.
</P>
<P>
"We must spend greater efforts in pushing the peace process
forward. There are some difficulties. We will overcome these
difficulties," Levy said at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Levy will proceed to Istanbul, the largest city
in Turkey, after concluding his contacts in Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
