<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Chance Exists to Revive Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said on
Tuesday that there still is a decent chance to revive peace talks
between Israel and the Palestinians despite the failure of his
effort to talk Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu into
abandoning housing construction in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"I would not conclude from the fact that I'm giving very
noncommital answers that we cannot get it (the Middle East peace
process) going again. I think there's a fairly decent chance that
we can," Clinton said at a White House joint news conference with
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian delegation headed by Hanan Ashrawi, a member of
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's Cabinet, was to come to
Washington for talks with U.S. officials over the Middle East
crisis, caused by Israel breaking ground in east Jerusalem for the
housing construction.
</P>
<P>
Clinton believed the talks would be another chance for the
reviving peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Chretien, speaking at the joint news conference after his talks
with Clinton, directed his criticism at Israel for the decision to
build the Jewish homes in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"Building new settlements in places that were not contemplated
by pre-existing agreements cannot be supported because there will
be a difficulty to achieve peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier at a photo session with Chretien, Clinton ruled out
the possibility that the United States would impose high pressure
on both sides to pull them back to the negotiating table,
disrupted by the Israel's settlement decision in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"I want these parties to do what they have to do to get this
process up and going again. We've got to have an atmosphere of
zero tolerance for terror, but we've also got to have the kind
of confidence-guilding necessary to make peace," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
