<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugees Are Vulnerable to AIDS, UN Agency Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Refugees and displaced
people are more vulnerable to AIDS, a UN agency reported here
today.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) said that there
are around 40 million refugees and other displaced people in the
world today. Forced from their original homes by such emergencies
as flood, earthquake, war or civil strife, they are often living
in special camps and some of them have remained displaced for over
20 years.
</P>
<P>
As 75 percent of all refugees and displaced people are women
and children, AIDS threatens most. However, it is often overlooked
in the immediate wake of a disaster because there seem to be more
important things to do.
</P>
<P>
A serious danger for the spread of HIV lies in transfusion of
HIV-infected blood as transfusions are often needed in large
numbers in situations of war, strife and other emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Sexual contact presents another risk in an emergency as many of
them lose their families, regular sexual partners, possessions and
source of income. Moreover, woman refugees risk possible sexual
violence, rape and trafficking.
</P>
<P>
In areas where drug injecting occurred before the emergency, it
is likely to continue in camps, UNAIDS noted.
</P>
<P>
UNAIDS suggested that relief workers follow universal medical
precautions, condoms be made available early in an emergency,
relief agencies provide information on HIV risks and safer sex,
health services be set up after the acute phase of an emergency,
and refugees be protected from violence and abuse.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Seeks More Money to Combat Internet Child Pornography </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- FBI Director Louis Freeh
Tuesday said that his agency is trying hard to protect children
from the "dark side" of the Internet, where pedophiles search for
victims.
</P>
<P>
But Freeh and Ernest Allen, president of the National Center
for Missing &AMP; Exploited Children, said law enforcement needs more
money to deal with the problem, which has increased along with the
popularity of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"It's more of a resource issue for us and other agencies,"
Freeh told the Senate Appropriations subcommittee that oversees
funding of the Justice Department, the parent agency of the FBI.
"I think we have the tools there. I just think we need more
resources."
</P>
<P>
"The dark side of that technology is that criminals or
pedophiles can reach into your home... without many, many
safeguards," Freeh said.
</P>
<P>
Freeh said the FBI was attacking the problem through its
"Crimes Against Children" initiative, which covers sexual
exploitation of children, abductions and violent crimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
