<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zairian Rebels Enter Lubumbashi as Fighting Rages On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Zaire's rebels entered the country's
"economic lung" Lubumbashi this afternoon while fighting was
raging on between the rebels and the elite Special Presidential
Division of the Zairian army, reported Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Kyungu ku Mwanza, governor of the province of Shaba, of which
Lubumbashi is the capital, was seen circulating around the town on
a vehicle with a white flag in his hand by 15:30 (1330 GMT), said
AFP quoting witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Fierce fighting went on today between the rebels and government
troops over the control of the headquarters of the Special
Presidential Division, and the rebels have apparently taken it,
said AFP.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have put the southern part of the city under their
control by the afternoon, while government troops continued to
resist from other parts of the city with heavy weapons.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that many government soldiers were fleeing toward an
airport 10 kilometers north of Shaba, while the rebels were seen
to be moving near the airport in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
United States presidential spokesman Michael McCurry said today
that Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko "is on the point of
becoming a creature of history."
</P>
<P>
France today regretted that the peace talks between the rebels
and the government of Zaire in South Africa have failed to fix any
date for a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The fall of Lubumbashi will let the rebels control all the
major cities of Zaire, except the capital Kinshasa, and will let
them control most of the mineral resources of the country.
</P>
<P>
Situated 1,500 kilometers southeast of Kinshasa and 30
kilometers from the Zambian border, Lubumbashi is located on the
strategic position linking Zaire with the southern part of the
African continent.
</P>
<P>
Formerly called Elizabethville, Lubumbashi has around 740,000
inhabitants, according to a census made in 1984.
</P>
<P>
About 10 percent of the world's copper reserve and 80 percent
of its cobalt reserve are concentrated in Shaba along an arch
shaped land of 50 kilometers wide and 300 kilometers long
extending from Kolwesi in the northwest to Lubumbashi in the
southeast while passing through the city of Likasi.
</P>
<P>
Zaire's national mineral society Gecamines used to produce
470,000 tons of copper, 14,000 tons of cobalt and 65,000 tons of
zinc each year, earning the bulk of the country's foreign currency
income.
</P>
<P>
With the capture of Lubumbashi, the rebels are controlling the
minerally rich province of Shaba and the diamond-bearing province
of eastern Kasai, whose capital Mbuji-Mayi fell last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The rebels captured Zaire's third largest city Kisangani in
March, and are controlling the water traffic of the Zaire River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 32nd Chamber of Commerce World Congress Opens in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The 32nd World Congress of the
International Chamber of Commerce (ICC) opened in Shanghai this
morning, with more than 1,000 participants from 74 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
This is China's first ICC congress since the ICC was founded in
1919.
</P>
<P>
The theme is "Asia in Global Economy". Participants will
discuss the global economy, Asian entrepreneurs' views on the
world market, China's increasing role in Asia and the world, the
economic development of Shanghai and Hong Kong, and ICC policies.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng, speaking at the opening ceremony,
welcomed the participants and wished the meeting success on behalf
of the Chinese government and people.
</P>
<P>
Li said that in today's world, multi-polarization is speeding
up, science and technology are seeing tremendous development, the
world economy is on the rise, international trade and investment
are expanding, economic links among countries are becoming closer,
and regional economic cooperation is increasing.
</P>
<P>
He pointed particularly to accelerating economic growth in some
developing countries, but said that the world is still full of
conflicts and has imbalanced economic development and a growing
gap between the rich and the poor. There are also unfair exchanges
that harm the rights and interests of developing countries, he
said, and there is a common appeal of people all over the world
for a fairer and more rational order in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that Asia, which has experienced various hardships,
has many remarkable economic achievements, especially in East
Asia, which has been a leader in world economic growth for quite a
few years, and has been a force for economic growth in the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
The Asian people are striving to bring a peaceful, stable,
prosperous, and progressive Asia to the next century, Li said,
adding that potential for Asian development is great and Asia's
future is bright.
</P>
<P>
After speaking on the great changes resulting from China's
reform and opening up policy, Li said that China is closely tied
to Asia's prosperity and attributed China's achievements to the
reform and opening-up policy.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China will offer a 700-billion-US-dollar market in
the next four years, and that he hopes all far-sighted
entrepreneurs and businessmen will not miss the opportunity to
enter the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to the motherland on July 1 this year,
Hong Kong is bound to play a more active role in increasing
economic and trade relations among Asian countries, and between
Asia and the rest of the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
China is ready, on the basis of equality and reciprocity, to
strengthen cooperation and exchanges with Asian countries and
other countries, and to contribute to world peace and development,
he said.
</P>
<P>
This afternoon, Li met with ICC Chairman Helmut Maucher, ICC
officials, and foreign participants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
