<HEADLINE> Iraqi Plane Lands in Jeddah Defying UN Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 9 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi aircraft with 104
pilgrims on board landed today at the airport of Jeddah, Saudi
Arabia, breaking the U.N. ban of flights in and out of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Two Saudi Arabian warplanes intercepted and escorted the Iraqi
aircraft to Saudi western city of Jeddah and allowed the
passengers to complete necessary entry formalities for performing
Hajj in Mecca.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Interior Minister Prince Nayef Bin Abdel-Aziz was quoted
by Kuwait News Agency as saying that "two Saudi warplanes
intercepted the Iraqi aircraft, entering the Saudi airspace
without advance notice, at 12:00 local time. Realizing that the
aircraft had pilgrims aboard, the warplanes escorted the aircraft
to the airport to end entry formalities."
</P>
<P>
The minister said his country would not refuse any person
arriving for pilgrimage using whatever means of transportation.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council has imposed several
sanctions on Iraq after the Gulf War including a denial of
permission to any aircraft to take off or land in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the Iraqi plane took off from Iraq's
Rashid Air Base, which is about 15 kilometers south of the capital
of Baghdad, after holding a departure ceremony at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia was one of the major allies fighting against Iraq
in the 1990 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
About two million Muslims are expected to arrive in Saudi
Arabia to perform this year's Hajj. During the Hajj, Muslim
pilgrims will march to Mount Arafat, the site of the Prophet
Mohammad's last sermon 14 centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
Pilgrims have been arriving in the kingdom for weeks. Many
Iraqi pilgrims arrived last Monday by land to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, according to quota, can send up to 20,000 pilgrims every
year while every other Islamic countries was allowed to send up
to 1000 pilgrims for every 1 million citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
