<HEADLINE> France-China Trade Development Speeding Up: Says Consul General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- French Consul General in Shanghai
Gean-Pierre Bourrel, speaking with Shanghai's "Opening Drive"
monthly recently, said that the development of French-Chinese
trade is speeding up and that the momentum is good.
</P>
<P>
He recalled taking office here in September 1994, when there
were 250 French people working and living in Jiangsu and Zhejiang
provinces and Shanghai municipality, and that the number has now
increased to 570.
</P>
<P>
The number of French-backed ventures in the region has gone up
from 80 to 130, and there are 50 representative French offices, he
said. The two sides have entered an era of industrial cooperation
involving both multinationals and small and medium-sized
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Bourrel said that the next century will be a time for
strengthening cooperation between Europe and Asia, and that the
French government is paying particular attention to French-Chinese
economic and cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
President Chirac's upcoming visit scheduled for May is a good
indication of that, he noted. 
</P>
