<HEADLINE> Canada's Auto Sales Up 5 percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada's auto sales rose 5.1
percent in February to reach 111,377 units, Statistics Canada said
today.
</P>
<P>
February's rise nearly reversed the 5.8 percent decline seen in
January. Early indications of March sales suggest a month-to-month
gain in both cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
Truck sales remained highly variable. An 8.3 percent jump in
February followed a decline of 11.3 percent in January and an 11.6
percent increase in December.
</P>
<P>
But overall, the major trend in truck sales was upwards, the
federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
Car sales, which have been on the rise since April 1996,
increased 2.4 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
In the month, Canadian consumers spent an average of 18,700
U.S. dollars (before tax) on a motor vehicle, 5.7 percent more
than they spent a year ago, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
