<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Union Seek Shorter Working Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Germany's biggest union, IG Metall,
today proposed a shorter working week in a bid to create more jobs
to tackle the country's problem of high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The union would seek the introduction of a 32-hour, four-day
week in its scheduled pay talks with employers in 1999, said Klaus
Zwickel, head of IG Metall, at a union-sponsored employment summit
in Berlin. The union has about 2.7 million members.
</P>
<P>
He said IG Metall would focus its efforts on this issue in the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 40 years, IG Metall has been a leader in the
drive for shorter working hours. It pushed through a 40-hour,
five-day week 30 years ago, and a 35-hour week that began in
October 1995 in the western German metal and engineering
industries, after 20-years of effort.
</P>
<P>
Zwickel made the proposal after official data released on
Tuesday showed that Germany's unemployment remained high at about
4.48 million in March, though 195,000 down from a postwar record
high of 4.67 million in February.
</P>
<P>
The IG Metall chief, in 1995, urged an "Alliance for Jobs"
between unions, employers and the government. It called for low
wage increases in return for jobs creation.
</P>
<P>
However, the alliance broke up last year after unions
criticized the government for its attempts to cut welfare and work
related benefits in a bid to keep public spending within limits
set for joining Europe's single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
At the Berlin summit, Zwickel also warned that any delay to the
planned 1999 launch of the euro would lead to a stronger German
mark and subsequently further weakened labor market in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Dieter Schulte, head of the German trade union federation
(DGB), welcomed IG Metall's proposal. He renewed his appeal for
inclusion of social and employment goals in the European Union's
Maastricht treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
