<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Love or Hate, No More Free Rides at Great </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 9 (Xinhua) -- "It really pays to take a free ride
at the last of the surviving Seven Wonders of the World," sighed
Xia Peng, a Chinese tourist who came to admire the great pyramids
and ended up lamenting his adventure.
</P>
<P>
Xia, dragged onto the horseback by an enthusiastic horse owner
a couple of minutes ago, narrowly escaped a free fall from a
precipice as several animals jostled for space on a narrow pass
leading to the Sphinx.
</P>
<P>
Still reeling from a sound horse bite on the hip, Xia finally
gave in the horse riding and placed a few more pounds into the
man's stretched hands for taking picture with his scrubby camel.
</P>
<P>
However, if tourists like Xia know that their days of free
riding at the Pyramids are numbered, they would rather appreciate
the free-wheeling Egyptian camel and horse drivers that lull them
with a promised joyful ride, then bargain for pay in the hard way.
</P>
<P>
The government recently approved a plan to develop the Giza
plateau south of Cairo aimed at keeping tourist buses, cars and
animals afar from the area.
</P>
<P>
A 10-kilometer "tourist ring road," including parking places, a
cultural and recreational center and a new station for camels,
horses and horse-drawn carts will be built just south of the
pyramids.
</P>
<P>
The stable, equipped with a veterinary clinic, will sit two
kilometers south of the smallest pyramid within two months and
will serve as base for the drivers.
</P>
<P>
Zahi Hawass, Director of the Pyramids Antiquities
Administration, upholds the plan to shoo the drivers away from the
Giza pyramids as part of a clean-up campaign.
</P>
<P>
"The camels and horses are shitting and peeing in the area and
destroying the monuments. They have a golden plate and instead
they shit in it," Hawass said.
</P>
<P>
Hawass said he was determined to rid the pyramids of "sight
pollution" and "create a dignified atmosphere to enjoy them."
</P>
<P>
Even if the fun of riding close to the pyramids will be taken
away, tourists and tourist guides agree reorganization is needed
for the benefit of the Giza plateau.
</P>
<P>
But, the camel and horse drivers are furious at the plans by
the Egyptian authorities and threatened to file a lawsuit to fight
out their right for the ancient profession.
</P>
<P>
At "panorama point," where tourist buses discharge hundreds of
tourists daily for a picture-perfect view of the pyramids, anger
is boiling.
</P>
<P>
"We filed a suit at the administrative court against Hawass a
month ago," according to Sayed Fathi Abdou, one of the 500 camel
and horse drivers about to lose their vintage spot.
</P>
<P>
"First they removed us from the foot of the pyramids to the
`panorama' and now they want to throw us into the desert and kill
our livelihood," he said.
</P>
<P>
"More than 15,000 families live on this business. It will mean
our death," said Ali Salama, who fears competition from unlicensed
drivers riding in from the desert.
</P>
<P>
Billed by some as a nuisance and a stigma on the Egyptian
reputation, the horse and camel drivers, however, are still widely
accepted as part of the site and authentic Oriental culture.
</P>
<P>
Sayed Mohammed Ghanem, who inherited his camel trade from his
father and grandfather, said "The pyramids and the camel cannot be
dissociated."
</P>
<P>
The tourist police chief for the pyramids area, Mohammed Al
Sheikh, dismissed their fears and said the police presence will
ensure everyone an equal opportunity.
</P>
<P>
"There are 4,200 tombs in the area, only 19 of which are open
to the public, and the horses and the camel tread on the unopened
tombs and damage them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, the surrounding area around the pyramids will become
cleaner and quieter without the animals, though the forthcoming
tourists will lose a chance to experience their adventure as Xia
did. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
