<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Actions Imperative to Meet Development Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 9 (Xinhua) -- South Asian countries should
take concrete steps in the next 15 years to reduce the widening
gaps in human development between them and East Asian nations, a
report on human development in South Asia says.
</P>
<P>
The report issued here today by the Human Development Center
says that both regions had similar income levels in the 1960s, but
East Asia now has a nominal per capita income 27 times greater
than South Asia's, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report prepares detailed estimates for implementing a
concrete human priority agenda in South Asia over the next 15
years.
</P>
<P>
The agenda includes providing universal primary education,
basic health care, safe drinking water for the entire population,
adequate nutrition for malnourished children, family planning
services to 80 percent of married couples, and credit facilities
for the poorest sections of society.
</P>
<P>
The report estimates that the total cost of such a human
development package would amount to approximately 130 billion U.S.
dollars over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The report also suggests the South Asian countries should
reduce their defense spending and their massive domestic debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
