<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmer Keeps 43-Year Promise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The reason 59-year-old Liu Houqi,
a farmer in central China's Hunan Province, is so different from
his fellow villagers is that he has been a faithful observer of
meteorological phenomena for 43 years.
</P>
<P>
Liu took up weather forecasting in the spring of 1954 when he
was a farmer in Fengwei Village of Liuyang City. The township is
located at the foot of a 1,600-meter-high mountain. Because of its
location, the township was not covered by a weather forecasting
system, and residents often fell victim to the weather's whimsies.
</P>
<P>
Liu, who had only two and a half years of schooling, swore that
he would win out in the struggle with the Heavens. So, he made a
precipitation gauge out of bamboo and fashioned a thermometer. He
bought books and gathered proverbs to enrich his knowledge about
the field.
</P>
<P>
To warn villagers of weather changes, he put up a sign board by
the road and put two flags up on a hill -- a red one meaning
"clear sky," and a green one signifying "rain."
</P>
<P>
In 1964, Liu joined the Communist Party of China and acquired a
make-shift weather station with the help of the county weather
station.
</P>
<P>
Rain or shine, winter and summer, Liu Houqi goes to the weather
station three times a day. As an example of his dedication, one
day, it was not until he had returned home from the station that
he learned that his mother had passed away.
</P>
<P>
In mid-June of 1995, Liu forecast heavy flooding 48 hours in
advance, after a week of observations and analysis. He rushed the
report to the local radio station, asking residents to be
prepared. As a result, no one was killed when the flood, the
biggest in 100 years, hit.
</P>
<P>
In the past 43 years, Liu has made more than 250 correct
weather forecasts, and his degree of accuracy has climbed from an
unimpressive 30 percent to over 80 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
