<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Imports of German and Dutch Pigs and Cows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Agriculture
recently issued a directive strictly prohibiting the import of
pigs, cows, and related products from Germany and the Netherlands
to prevent the spread of infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
According to an official from China's Animal and Plant
Quarantine Administration, hog cholera wreaked havoc in Germany
in January. Some 30,000 pigs were killed as a result, and the
disease is now still spreading in the country.
</P>
<P>
In February, swine fever cases were discovered in the
Netherlands, and there was a report of mad cow disease in the
country in March.
</P>
<P>
To protect China's livestock industry, the state has decided to
ban the import of live pigs, pork and all related products from
Germany. Any such items brought into or shipped to China will be
confiscated and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The rule is also effective for imported pigs, pork, and related
products from the Netherlands. In addition, cattle, calves, beef,
and related products are also prohibited.
</P>
<P>
All confiscated items must be destroyed under the supervision
of animal and plant quarantine offices, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
