<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Experts Arrive in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- A 54-member nuclear experts team
from a multi-national consortium arrived today in the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) to negotiate the building of
nuclear reactors in the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The team of the Korean Peninsula Energy Development
Organization (KEDO), is a consortium led the United States, South
Korea and Japan, which was formed under a 1994 nuclear deal. It
arrived in the eastern coastal city of Sinpo by ship from the
South Korean eastern port of Tonghae.
</P>
<P>
The main task of the team is to discuss the implementation of
the agreement between KEDO and the DPRK on providing two
light-water reactors to the DPRK, and technological problems over
building the reactors.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed in 1994, KEDO will build two
1,000-megawatt light-water reactors for the DPRK to replace its
graphite-moderated reactors which could produce materials used for
making nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The reactors will be build in Sinpo.
</P>
<P>
The expert team comprising 40 South Koreans, three
U.S. delegates, three Japanese and eight KEDO staff will stay in
the DPRK until April 15.
</P>
<P>
During the stay, the experts will survey the infrastructure for
building the reactors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
