<HEADLINE> Netherlands Invites OSCE Leaders to Mark Marshall Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok has
invited leaders of OSCE countries to commemorate the 50th
anniversary of the Marshall plan, the biweekly Atlantic News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
groups all European countries, the United States, Canada and
former republics of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The Marshall Plan, named after George Marshall, then U.S.
secretary of state and later secretary of defense, was intended to
revive Europe from the ashes of World War II.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony will be held in The Hague on May 28.
</P>
<P>
On the same day in The Hague, the half-yearly European
Union-U.S. summit is planned, with the participation of the
current President of the European Council, Wim Kok, President of
the European Commission Jacques Santer and U.S. President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The commemoration could also be an occasion to bring together
leaders of the 16 NATO member countries and Russian President
Boris Yeltsin in order to sign, if possible, a document on future
relations between NATO and Russia, NATO sources said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of March, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
hinted, after meeting his Russian counterpart, Yevgeny Primakov,
that this document would be signed "at the highest level" and it
would be good to do this "around the 27th, 28th or 29th of May."
</P>
<P>
However, a "true battle" was being waged now over which town
will be chosen for the signing of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Also waiting in line are Paris, and Denver in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said today that Paris might be the venue to signing.
</P>
<P>
"If the document is ready, President Yeltsin could come to
Paris to sign this agreement," he told reporters after a meeting
with French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
But earlier there was also mention of Denver, where the leaders
of the Group of Seven industrialized nations and President Yeltsin
will meet in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
