<HEADLINE> Egypt expects Visit to Mideast by Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mubarak's political advisor Osama el-Baz made the statement to
reporters, two days after apparently tough White House talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu have achieved no
immediate breakthrough in restarting the stalled Mideast peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "Washington is currently probing the views of
the Palestinian and Israeli sides," referring to the Monday
meeting between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Netanyahu and the
upcoming visits to Washington by Palestinian senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is sending Cabinet Minister
Hanan Ashrawi to meet with Albright and Ross tomorrow to present
his view on the Jewish settlement and Jerusalem, a key to the
solution of the Palestinian-Israeli conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas and top Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat will also go to Washington on a follow-up mission
after Netanyahu returned to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Baz said if any progress materializes, Ross will visit the
region next week to meet with Netanyahu, Arafat and leaders in the
Mideast region, particularly Egypt. Albright was scheduled to
visit the region from April 25 to 28.
</P>
<P>
Because of huge differences between the Palestinians and
Israelis, the Clinton administration has failed to bring the two
sides to a face-to-face talks with a new initiative that will
press Netanyahu to stop the building Jewish settlement in East
Jerusalem and urge Arafat to curb Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have ceased and violence has
erupted nearly every day since Israel launched construction for a
6,500-home new Jewish housing project in Arab East Jerusalem last
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
