<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik Peace Talks Open in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between the Tajik
government and its opposition opened here today, which will focus
on negotiation about a political and a military protocol.
</P>
<P>
Talabak Nazarov, Tajik Foreign Minister and head of the seven-
member delegation, expressed optimism on the outcome of the
negotiations toward peace in Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
He said that today's talks are the third meeting on the issue
of peace in the Tajikistan in a bid to achieve the national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would work hard with the opposition group to
reach agreement on some important issues.
</P>
<P>
Akbar Turajonzada, head of the seven-member opposition group,
stressed the freedom of political parties and their activities at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said that "we are at the final stage of the negotiations."
He expressed the hope that there will be peace in Tajikistan. The
opposition should be able to engage in political activities, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, not all provisions of the previous documents
have been materialized, specially pertaining to an amnesty since
some opposition members were executed by the government.
</P>
<P>
"We ask the observer countries and those who are involved in
the negotiations to do their best to see that the Tajik government
would undertake all its responsibilities as far as implementation
of the provisions of previous protocols are concerned," he added.
</P>
<P>
As observers, Iran, Russia, Pakistan and Uzbekistan
participated the meeting which was presided over by U.N. envoy for
Tajik affairs Gerd Merriam.
</P>
<P>
Voicing Iran's willingness to help bring an end to the
critical situation in Tajikistan, Iranian Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati reiterated that Iran is ready to help and provide
facilities to both belligerent sides to solve problems of the
Tajik nation.
</P>
<P>
He urged both the Tajik government and the opposition to
remove the existing obstacles and restore peace and tranquility
to the country through peaceful negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Velayati stressed that a powerful and independent Tajikistan
is vital for stability in Central Asia as well as in the whole
region.
</P>
<P>
Several rounds of official and unofficial Tajik peace talks
have been held in the Iranian capital of Tehran, Moscow and
Ashkhabad of Russia, and Islamabad of Pakistan to date. This is
the third time for Tehran to host such talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
