<HEADLINE> UNITA Parliament Members' Swearing in Positively </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The swearing in of the parliament
members of the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) received positive responses from political
personnel who were invited to observe the swearing ceremony
today.
</P>
<P>
Special representative of the United Nations and mediator for
Angola peace process Blonoin Beye said to reporters that today
and April 11 on which the government of national unity and
reconciliation will swear in are both special days marking a
milestone in the history of Angola and drawing the attention of
all Angolan people.
</P>
<P>
UNITA leader Jorge Valentim who will take the post as minister
of tourism said that Angola peace process has turned on a new
page beginning from today and all politicians should make joint
effort to strengthen national reconciliation and create a happy
life for the Angolan people.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador of the United States to Angola Donald Steinbeg
expressed satisfaction with today's swearing in, saying that this
showed the "political courage" of the UNITA leaders. Brazilian
ambassador Addor Neto stressed the very importance of the event,
saying that this not only completed the parliament but would also
infuse enthusiasm into parliament debates.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Opposition Party spokesman Pinto Joao said that the
swearing in of UNITA parliament members had made the Angola
Democracy more representative. The Luanda Cathalic church bishop
Alexandre Do Nascimento expressed the hope that the Angolan
politicians will not disappoint the people in their longing for
peace. 
</P>
