<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Becomes World's Major Ore Consumer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Development of China's iron and
steel industry requires that the country import more iron ore,
making China one of the world's major iron ore consumers following
Japan and Europe.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from China's Ministry of Metallurgical
Industry, China produced 250 million tons of iron ore last
year. The output this year is estimated to be slightly higher.
</P>
<P>
China's steel production last year broke the benchmark of 100
million tons. Local experts estimated that the annual output is to
reach 120 million tons by the end of this century, and 140 million
tons in 2005.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China's steel consumption growth may average 4.3
percent in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
Local experts have so far predicted that China in the future
will rely more on imported high-grade iron ore to support the
sustained development of the country's iron and steel industry.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that China began to import a large quantity
of iron ore in the mid-1980s. The import volume of high-grade iron
ore in 1986 was 12 million tons. The figure leapt to 43.87 million
tons last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
