<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has approved the establishment of 28 new
investment projects with a total capital of 135 million Egyptian
pounds (39.7 million U.S. dollars), said the Egyptian Gazette
today.
</P>
<P>
The projects comprised 26 industrial projects in spinning and
weaving, clothes and engineering industries, foodstuff and
furniture and electrical appliances, said Ibrahim Fawzi, chief
of General Investment Authority executive body Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Twelve projects to be located in the less-developed southern
provinces are expected to generate 2,124 new jobs, while another
six in the new communities will provide 1,644 job opportunities, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which adopted an investment law in 1989, has bent on
encouraging new projects to create more jobs.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has decided to privatize its seed producing
companies on the condition that the state still fully controls
the seed production, a corner stone of the agricultural
production process, the Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Agriculture and Land Reclamation Youssef
Wali made the statement Tuesday in a speech at a two-day
symposium on seed production and the privatization of the state
seed companies.
</P>
<P>
Egypt started to liberalize the agricultural sector in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Foreign investment from January to March this year
rose by 17.5 percent in Turkey, according to figures from the
Treasury.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Daily News today quoted Treasury officials
as saying that the total investment approved amounted to 124
million U.S. dollars for March, bringing the total investment
for the first three months this year to 375 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The major investors are from European Union countries with a
total investment of 269.6 million dollars, and countries of the
Organization for Economic and Cooperation Development rank next,
whose investment stands at 74.7 million dollars, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The figures issued by the Treasury showed that the
manufacturing sector was the main area of interest for foreign
investors, which has attracted around 255.7 million dollars worth
of investment.
</P>
<P>
The number of foreign firms investing in Turkey has risen to
3,691, with a total capital of 1.73 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A new cable under the Gulf sea waters linking
Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will
start operation in July this year, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The 1,350-kilometer-long cable called "Fog" would provide high
technological services in transmitting video, audio and facsimile
signals, in addition to providing data for all computers and
Internet users in the four countries, said the sources from
the Kuwaiti Communication Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The cable was also designed to link with other international
cables like "Flag" which will stretch through the Red Sea and
Arabian Sea to Europe after it comes into operation by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Linking Fog and Flag will connect the Gulf with Japan, China,
Thailand, Malaysia, India, Egypt, Italy, Spain, Britain and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the cable was designed to live for up to 25
years, but studies show that it might serve for 50 years without
regular maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The cable runs from Kuwait through Bahrain and Qatar all
the way to the UAE. Saudi Arabia has also requested to join
the cable, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
