<HEADLINE> Two Suspects Returned to Hong Kong from Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Two crime suspects wanted by
Hong Kong police were returned today from south China's Guangdong
Province, a Hong Kong government press release said.
</P>
<P>
They were the first batch of crime suspects returned by
Guangdong this year.
</P>
<P>
Officers from the Hong Kong Interpol Bureau and detectives from
the Royal Hong Kong Police took custody of the two suspects at a
ceremony held at a border control office in the southern Chinese
city of Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Yeung Wan-kam and Lam Wing-sing, aged 39 and 29, were involved
in a homicide case which occurred in Wan Chai, on Hong Kong
island, two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The pair had been hiding in Guangdong and were arrested by
police in Zhuhai, Guangdong Province, during a gambling raid in
March this year.
</P>
<P>
Through Hong Kong Interpol, their wanted status were confirmed
and arrangements with the counterparts in Guangdong Province for
their return were made.  
</P>
