<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Vows to Keep Nuclear Options Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- India will keep its nuclear
options open until there is total elimination of nuclear weapons
in the world, the Defense Ministry said in an annual report today.
</P>
<P>
Defending India's refusal to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty (CTBT), the report said the treaty was neither a measure
for nuclear disarmament nor was it comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
Mere preventive or punitive actions on a selective and ad hoc
basis could not achieve the desired results towards elimination of
nuclear weapons, it said.
</P>
<P>
The CTBT was adopted by the United Nations General Assembly on
September 10, 1996, and was open for signatures later in the
month. But India and several other countries refused to sign it.
</P>
<P>
The ministry report defended New Delhi's decision to develop
its own nuclear capacity and vowed to withstand occasional
international pressures against its missile program.
</P>
<P>
"The indigenous development of missile capability by India is
in response to the evolving security environment in its
region. The countries seeking to impose restraints on India have
also continued their nuclear weapons and missile research
programs," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Fissile Materials Cut-off Treaty, currently under
negotiation in Geneva, might also perpetuate the supremacy of the
nuclear weapon states unless it was placed in the framework of
universal and comprehensive disarmament, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Keeps Climbing Against Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States dollar continued
its climb against the Japanese yen in Tokyo today amid a growing
perception among investors that neither Japan nor the United
States will take any immediate action to stem the yen's slide.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo exchange market, the dollar was traded at 126.87
yen at midday, its highest level in four-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the dollar was changing hands at 126.65-67 yen, up
from 126.09-12 yen at 9 a.m., and from 126.25-35 yen in New York.
</P>
<P>
The yen could slip further in the coming weeks, given the
widening gap between interest rates in Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Japanese rates are at record lows, while the Federal Reserve is
widely expected to bump American interest rates up even higher
next month, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
On Tokyo Stock Exchange, share prices declined sharply under
profit-taking pressure, along with continued weaknesses of
banking, brokerage and constitution issues.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected stocks closed at a session
low of 17,703.37, slipping 318.33 points or 1.77 percent from
Tuesday's end.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the first session was about 410 million shares, down
from the previous day's 477.50 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
