<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sees Double-Digit Growth of GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Recent statistics show that the
total gross domestic product (GDP) in Shanghai, China's largest
city, has reached 68.6 billion yuan in the first quarter of this
year, up 13.5 from the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The city's GDP in March also increased by a double-digit rate
to 15.5 percent, on a year-on-year basis, with its total
industrial output value hitting 45.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has seen brisk sales of retail goods since the start
of this year. The total value of retailed goods reached 33.5
billion yuan in the first quarter, up 17.2 percent from the same
period the year before.
</P>
<P>
The figure of retail products was 10.7 billion yuan last month,
up 18.7 percent from March 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city's total exports surged 13 percent from
March 1996, standing at 1.3 billion US dollars. And the combined
export value of the city in the past three months reached 3.3
billion dollars, an increase of 10.4 percent from the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
But the prices of daily consumption goods rose only by an
average of 3.9 percent in the first quarter, and the prices of
retailed commodities by only one percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
