<HEADLINE> 130 More KNU Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- About 130 more members of the Kayin
National Union (KNU), the largest anti-government ethnic armed
group in Myanmar, surrendered to the government in Kayin state
last month, official sources confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
The authorities said the KNU members, which are from a unit
under the group's 6th Brigade led by captain Sein Hlaing, "traded
their arms for peace" in the Kya-in-Seikyi township.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier official report, more than 500 members
of the KNU had surrendered in Kawkareik, Myawaddy and
Kya-in-Seikyi areas of the same state in February following the
government's mopping-up operations there.
</P>
<P>
The KNU is the only remaining one of the 16 anti-government
ethnic armed groups, which has not yet to make peace with the
government despite four rounds of peace talks held with the
government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
