<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eco-Zone Paints Rosy Picture for Future Agriculture in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Amid the rolling plains of
central Henan Province, China's major granary, lies a 310-ha
experiment zone of ecological agriculture which is exploring a
modern agro-production style of sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
The pilot zone, located in Youfang Township, Fengqiu County, is
currently the biggest eco-agriculture zone in China, said Chang
Yuncheng, Director of Henan Provincial Agricultural Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Within the eco-agro zone, square-shaped fields lie between
roads, irrigation ditches and surrounding trees.
</P>
<P>
Next to the fields are white plastic greenhouses used to grow
vegetables in winter. Rows of fish ponds are nearby.
</P>
<P>
The experimental zone, featuring the varied topography of north
China, includes 231 ha of farmland, 50 ha of fish ponds and 46 ha
of vegetable gardens. Construction of the zone, expected to be
completed next year, will cost 4.6 million yuan. Its annual output
is estimated at 8.5 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Low cost but high yield is typical of the ecological zone,
which agricultural experts say represents a trend for future
agriculture: sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
Through comprehensive cultivation and sophisticated
utilization, the farmland in the zone is expected to produce 1.5
tons of grain each year. In the fish ponds, ducks and fish
co-exist and vegetables grow well in the sunny plastic greenhouses.
</P>
<P>
Co-existence, co-reliance and good nutrition are secrets behind
the successful zone, said Li Arong, fertilizer specialist and
research fellow with the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The technology-intensive eco-zone will test all kinds of
advanced farming techniques and pool experts to guide farmers'
production, Li said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
