<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Chief Executive's Office Seek Suggestions on Ordinances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive's Office of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) today issued a
consultation document to solicit public views on proposals to
amend the Societies Ordinance and the Public Order Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing held here this morning, Michael Suen,
secretary for policy coordination at the HKSAR Chief Executive's
Office, urged members of the community to freely express their
views on the suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Suen said that the HKSAR Government is committed to the
continued protection of human rights and personal freedoms as
provided for in the Basic Law and in the international covenants
which are applicable to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said, "However we must also strike a balance between civil
liberties and social stability, personal rights and social
obligations, individual interests and the common good."
</P>
<P>
On February 23 this year, the Standing Committee of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC) resolved, under Article 160 of
the Basic Law, that three sections of the Hong Kong Bill of
Rights Ordinance and the major amendments to the Societies
Ordinance (SO) and the Public Order Ordinance (POO) introduced in
1992 and 1995 respectively shall not be adopted as the laws of
the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Suen said that the document aims to invite public comments on
proposals to amend the SO and POO to fill the legal vacuum
resulting from the NPC's resolution.
</P>
<P>
He said, "In working out the proposals, we adhere to the
principle that they must be in full compliance with the Basic Law
and consistent with the provisions of the International Covenant
on Civil and Political Rights.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We believe the proposals put forward in the
consultation document have struck a fine balance between
protecting individual rights and freedoms and maintaining the
stability of the community.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We shall be meeting members of the Municipal Councils
and District Boards, as well as major political parties and
interest groups to explain our proposals."
</P>
<P>
The consultation will end on April 30 and draft legislation
will be prepared for the Provisional Legislative Council to
consider in the light of the views expressed during the public
consultation, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
