<HEADLINE> UNITA Parliament Members Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Parliament members of the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) were
officially sworn in today at the National Assembly, thus bringing
about the formal formation of the Assembly born through the 1992
elections.
</P>
<P>
During the first multi-party elections in 1992, UNITA
altogether won 70 seats in the parliament. Apart from three who
have so far not arrived in Luanda and one who is ill, all the
rest 66 members took part in today's swearing ceremony. Raising
their right hands high, they pledged to implement the Angolan
Constitution and other laws and work for peace, democracy and
social development.
</P>
<P>
UNITA parliament member Jeronimo Wanga was elected second
vice-speaker of the National Assembly at today's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
After the ceremony, dozens of Angolan children, in their best
holiday costumes and holding white roses and balloons symbolizing
peace, ran into the hall and danced joyous dances to express
their wishes for peace on behalf of all the Angolan children. In
the end, they presented the flowers to the UNITA parliament
members.
</P>
<P>
The current parliament was born through elections in 1992.
But the parliament members failed to take their posts due to
the civil war that broke out once again at the end of that
year. Today's swearing in is an important step in Angola's
peace process and also marked the formation of the National
Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
