<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sets New Rules for Offshore Financial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today tabled new
bills in Parliament setting new rules for its first International
Offshore financial Center (IOFC) in Labuan, a Federal Territory
off Sabah, east Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Both the Labuan Offshore Partnerships Bill 1997 and the bill
for amendments to the Offshore Insurance Act 1990 tabled today
aimed at enabling the further development of Labuan IOFC, the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Labuan Offshore Partnerships Bill 1997, an offshore
limited partnership will be allowed, which shall consist of not
less than two partners and not more than 20 partners.
</P>
<P>
The offshore professional partnership shall not carry on
practice except in one or more of the following fields such as
accounting, actuarial science, engineering, law or such other
fields as may be prescribed by the Labuan Offshore Financial
Services Authority (LOFSA), it provides.
</P>
<P>
The amendments to the Offshore Insurance Act 1990, among other
things, are aimed at reducing the minimum capital requirement to
obtain a licence to carry on an offshore insurance business to
300,000 ringgit (about 120,000 U.S. dollars) from one million
ringgit (about 400,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Out of over 1,000 offshore companies established in Labuan, 11
are insurance and insurance-related companies.
</P>
<P>
The offshore insurance industry in Labuan saw significant
progress in 1996 when total assets increased more than three-fold
to 138.2 million dollars from 32.5 million dollars in 1995,
according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Labuan was declared as an IOFC of Malaysia's own in October
1990.
</P>
<P>
The moves were in line with efforts by the government to
develop Labuan as a premier IOFC with various financial products
and services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Jobless Rate to Remain Stable By 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's jobless rate is
expected to remain at 0.38 percent until the year 2000, the Thai
National Economic and Social Development Board predicts.
</P>
<P>
According to figures from the board, employment in the country
will reach 32.997 million this year, 175,000 more than 1996, while
the country's workforce will grow to 33.124 million from 32.948
million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 2000, the country's employment is expected to rise to 33.647
million and its workforce will swell to 33.777 million, keeping
the jobless rate stabilized at 0.38 percent.
</P>
<P>
The non-agriculture sector is expected to employ 17.838 million
people in 2000, an increase of 2.453 million jobs from 1996, but
employment in the agriculture sector is expected to decline to
15.809 million from 17.437 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The board also predicts that the country's total population
will hit 62.405 million in 2000 from 60.002 million in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
