<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Research Shows Chinese Astronomer First Found Jupiter's Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Jupiter's moon was sighted for the
first time by a Chinese astronomer about 2,300 years ago,
according to new research findings which dispute the belief that
Italian astronomer Galileo first spotted the satellite with a
telescope in 1609.
</P>
<P>
Findings in an ancient book on astrology show that Gan De, a
noted Chinese astronomer of the Warring States period (475-221
BC), viewed Jupiter with the naked eye and saw one of its 16 moons
in 364 BC.
</P>
<P>
Although Gan De's two astrological books have been lost, a book
from the Tang Dynasty (618-907) contains his description of
Jupiter and its satellite, Xi Zezong, a researcher at the Research
Institute of Natural Scientific History under Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS), told Xinhua News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The book quoted Gan De as saying that there was a small
light-red star near "big and bright" Jupiter in the summer sky,
and that they belonged to the same star system.
</P>
<P>
Xi inferred that the star was the planet's moon because of its
color, location and the time it appeared.
</P>
<P>
"It's possible that ancient people could find Jupiter's No.3
satellite if people's eyesight, time and other factors were suited
to such observation," said Xi, who is also an academician of CAS.
</P>
<P>
"Sky-watchers in ancient China should be able to distinguish
small satellites from Jupiter's brightness since they were both
diligent and skilled in star-gazing," he said, adding that the
records in the ancient book were reliable.
</P>
<P>
In order to prove Xi's theory, his research institute has
organized astronomers and amateur star-gazers to observe Jupiter's
satellites with their own eyes.
</P>
<P>
"They not only can see the red satellite, their observation
results were also identical with that which was gained by using
telescopes," Xi said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
