<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Progress in Asset, Capital Check-up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- China has made initial progress in
checking the assets and capital of urban collective enterprises,
according to sources at an ongoing national meeting.
</P>
<P>
A pilot program to evaluate the assets and capital of urban
collective enterprises, launched last year, covers 13,000 of the
urban companies including 588 large and medium-sized firms and
2,538 industrial firms.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary statistics show that those enterprises had a total
of 139.3 billion yuan in assets and 112 billion yuan in
liabilities, which translates into an asset-liability ratio of
80.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures also show that China had 495,000 urban collective
enterprises at the end of 1996, including 210,000 commercial and
trade businesses and 146,000 industrial firms.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Youcai, vice minister of finance, said that the
collective sector is an important basis of China's socialist,
public-owned economy.
</P>
<P>
As China deepens reform and accelerates its pace to build a
socialist market economy, the collective sector has become an
inseparable part of the national economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The effort to ascertain the asset value and capital stock of
the collective enterprises is a basic task to promote the reform
and development of the collective economy and is a large-scale
comprehensive survey of the national strength," he said.
</P>
<P>
Official data also show that the output and workforce of the
urban collective industry was about a quarter of those of the
whole urban industry in 1995, making it the second largest
economic force next only to the state-owned sector.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the pilot program should be expanded to cover
more than ten percent of the collective enterprises in all areas
and sectors, in order to create conditions for a full-scale asset
and capital check-up of urban enterprises next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
