<HEADLINE> Mandatory Jail to Be Imposed in Malaysia for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government will
press the Court for mandatory jail sentence on chief executive
officers of companies convicted of seriously damaging the
environment.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet at its weekly meeting viewed seriously
environmental damage caused by development work and would seek
mandatory jail as a deterrence, Minister of Science, Technology
and Environment Law Hieng Ding said today.
</P>
<P>
"The cabinet has directed the ministry to go for mandatory jail
sentence apart from fines because it feels that fines alone are
not enough as the polluters can afford to pay," he told reporters
here after the weekly cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Under the Environmental Quality Act 1974 which was amended in
1996, serious environmental polluters can be fined up to 100,000
ringgit (about 40,000 U.S. dollars) or sentenced to five years
jail or both. But so far no one has been jailed for causing
environmental damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
