<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Points of Consultative Document of HKSAR Chief Executive's Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Consultative Document issued
today by the Chief Executive's Office of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) proposes that societies should be
registered.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, the grounds on which registration
can be refused are restricted to those provided for in Article 22
of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights
(ICCPR).
</P>
<P>
The grounds are national security, public safety, public order,
protection of public health or morals, or protection of the rights
and freedoms of others, it says.
</P>
<P>
In line with the provisions of Article 23 of the Basic Law,
political organizations in Hong Kong are also prohibited from
establishing ties with those in foreign countries, it says.
</P>
<P>
The proposed amendments to the Public Order Ordinance in the
document are related to the holding of public processions.
</P>
<P>
While the present notification system is largely retained, a
public procession can be held only after the Commissioner of
Police receives notice of a procession and issues a Notice of No
Objection to the organizers, the document suggests.
</P>
<P>
In normal circumstances, the notices should reach the
Commissioner at least seven days before the processions are
scheduled to take place, but this deadline may be shortened to 48
hours in exceptional cases.
</P>
<P>
The document says that the grounds for prohibiting the holding
of public processions are limited to those provided for in article
21 of the ICCPR.
</P>
<P>
The document aims to solicit public views on proposals to amend
the Societies Ordinance and the Public Order Ordinance and the
consultations will end on April 30.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
