<HEADLINE> Indonesia Plans to Apply FDI System in All Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The electronic data interchange
(FDI) system will be installed in all Indonesian ports within the
three years, an official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"By 2000, all Indonesian ports will use the system," Director
General for Customs Soehardjo said.
</P>
<P>
This system is already operational in Malaysia, Hong Kong, the
Philippines and Australia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The system will be installed at the Tanjung Priok port, near
Jakarta, this year, he said, adding that equipping all ports in
Java island with the Edi system would cost 50 billion rupiah
(about 21 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Edi system handles documents, clears goods and completes
inspection much faster than the present system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
