<HEADLINE> HK Urged to Create New Share for Technology Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- A study of Hong Kong's
manufacturing industries has recommended creating the T share, a
new type of stock to serve as an inducement for investments in the
development of new and high technology, local media reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) researchers
commissioned by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council and the
Industry Department published the study's findings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Richard Lester, director of the MIT Industrial Performance
Center, said the creation of a new class of shares that will be
tradable in the local stock exchange would go a long way in
encouraging people to invest in technology-based enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The best way to raise capital for new technology industries is
to create T-shares which can easily be traded in the local bourse,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Francis Ho, director-general of industry, said that the idea is
very good, adding that the unwillingness to invest in new
technologies is a major weakness of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to local media's report, many venture investors in
Hong Kong would only invest in well-established industries and
very few investors are interested in companies that produce and
sell products which they have created.
</P>
<P>
The disinterest in firms which produce new products and
technologies will present major obstacles to Hong Kong's
manufacturing industries even as they continue to move across the
HK-Guangdong border.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Faces Heavy Task in Fighting TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is facing the threat
from the tuberculosis (TB) due to the effect of air pollution and
increasingly crowded conditions, according to medical experts.
</P>
<P>
Medical adviser of Hong Kong Tuberculosis, Chest and Heart
Diseases Association Chan Shiu-lun said worsening air pollution
and overcrowding had made it difficult to prevent the spread of
the disease.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong may have to struggle for more than 20 years
before it can successfully eradicate tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
The total number of TB cases reported last year was 6,501, down
only 18 percent from the 7,928 in 1976.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, the number of people who died of tuberculosis
last year was 310, down 45 percent from 568 in 1976.
</P>
<P>
A high incidence of tuberculosis was noted among people older
than 50 years old and about two-thirds of people infected with the
disease last year were male.
</P>
<P>
Chan said he hoped the number of tuberculosis cases would drop
an average of five percent annually from this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the best way to speed up the eradication of the disease
was by vaccination and better hygiene education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
