<HEADLINE> First Iraqi Airliner Heads for Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 9 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi airplane carrying 104
Iraqi pilgrims left here today for the Saudi port city of Jedda,
the first flight run by Iraq since an air ban was imposed on it
for its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Endowments and Religious Affairs Abdul-Munim
Ahmed Saleh told Xinhua that the Iraqis who flew to Jedda today
are aged people who cannot endure the trouble of traveling by road
from Baghdad to Holy Mecca. The passengers on board also include
40 women,
</P>
<P>
He added that none of the U.N. Security Council resolutions
legally forbid running such a flight, especially that it is
designed to enable people to do a religious duty well-known to the
entire world.
</P>
<P>
Saleh expressed the hope that the plane would get to its
destination safely and the world would understand the
religious and humanitarian purposes of the flight. 
</P>
