<HEADLINE> Iranian FM on Relations With Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati said here today that Iran will adopt a wait-and-see
attitude toward its ties with Germany upon the announcement of
the verdict on the Mykonos case by German court.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here today, Velayati attacked
the German court for using the testimony of some "questionable
characters" such as former Iranian president Abulhassan Banisadr,
who was accused by Tehran of having colluded with Iraq to topple
the Islamic regime.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in the Bonn-Tehran relations came after the German
court accused Iranian leaders, such as Leader of Islamic
Revolution Ali Khamenei and President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani of
issuing the order to kill former leader of Iran's outlawed
Kurdistan Democratic Party Sadeq Sharafkandi and three of his
companies at the Mykonos restaurant in Berlin on September 17,
1992.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said that Banisadr "actually hijacked a plane" from
Iran to France and "cooperated with" Iran's anti-government
organization called Mujahideen Khalp Organization, which is based
inside the Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
He said that Banisadr is wanted as a criminal in Iran to face
charges. "How could he be used as a witness," he asked.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said "our reaction would be self-possession and
dignity. The decision of a court that uses a person of the
character of Banisadr and is politicized can not affect us. We
believe in respect and mutuality."
</P>
<P>
"We want Germany to understand that Iran would not allow
other countries to decide for its foreign policy or trample its
honor," the Iranian foreign minister added.
</P>
<P>
"We don't need to have ties with a country that oversteps
over aspirations and principles. We recognize that the German
government is separate from the court. But our objection is to
the other issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
As a retaliation measure, Iranian judicial authorities have
already lodged a law suit against German companies for exporting
chemical weapons to Iraq during the Iraqi-Iranian war from 1980 to
1988.


09/04/97 9:56 GMT

