<HEADLINE> Uganda Urges Political Exiles to Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Ugandan official has urged
political exiles abroad to return home and appealed to them to
help restore peace, ''the New Vision'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
Martin Aliker, the State Minister for Foreign Affairs, told a
meeting of Acholi people held last weekend in London that the
Ugandan government will not harm the returning political exiles.
</P>
<P>
Despite some extent of insecurity in the north due to military
conflicts, he encouraged his audience to return to help restore peace
and develop the country.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to the questions in the meeting attended by
nearly 300 delegates including some former ministers.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government has cancelled death order to Joseph Kony, the
main leader of the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA), the state minister
revealed earlier.
</P>
<P>
LRA launched a ten-year military rebellion in northern
districts of Kitgum and Gulu where Acholi people live. IRA is one
of the three main rebel groups in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Martin Aliker contacted with Otti Lagony, one of the main field
commanders of LRA, for peace talks last year, but the peace attempt
was undermined by some Acholi exiles in Britain and other countries,
the state minister said. enditem

