<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Benin to Jointly Curb Cross-Border Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian and Beninoise police have
agreed in principle to work together as part of efforts to curb the
increasing crime rate at their borders, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement reached on Monday, the two countries
have agreed that securitymen from both sides should be allowed to
pursue criminals attempting to cross the borders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, securitymen of the country where the criminals have been
driven into should assist in apprehending such criminals.
</P>
<P>
Both Nigeria and Benin are members of the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS). The 16 ECOWAS member nations signed a
protocol years ago on the free movement of persons and goods among
them as a means to boost economic integration in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Criminals have since taken advantage of the protocol to traverse
borders for refuge while perpetrating such crimes as car theft,
illicit circulation of fire-arms, armed robbery and illicit
trafficking of drug and art works.
</P>
<P>
With such crimes quickly gaining ground in the member nations,
no country is now safe from the activities, according to
Nigeria's Head of State General Sani Abacha, who is also the
current ECOWAS chairman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
