<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, Australia to Bolster Economic Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and Australia today
expressed their firm conviction that economic and other forms of
cooperation between them will receive fresh impetus in the days
ahead.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation between the two countries will take a better shape
and the proposed joint commission will be a forward movement in
this direction," visiting Australian Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister for Trade Tim Fischer told a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who held a meeting with Bangladeshi Minister of
Commerce and Industry Tofael Ahmed this morning, said the talks
had been very "constructive".
</P>
<P>
He said the time is right for the two countries to set up a
joint commission to bolster economic and other links and added
that both sides are taking measures in that direction.
</P>
<P>
Tofael Ahmed said Fischer is the second highest level visit
from Australia to Bangladesh since the visit of former prime
minister Edward Whitlam in 1975.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two sides discussed bilateral, regional and
international issues of mutual concern and there was no area where
found any disagreement.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi minister also expressed gratitude to Australia
for supporting Bangladesh's bid for membership in the Indian ocean
rim.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, Fischer called on Bangladeshi Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina. Both sides agreed that friendship between
Australia and Bangladesh should be further consolidated.  
</P>
