<HEADLINE> Zambia Promises Non-Interference in Zairean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will not allow Zaire's
former Katangese rebels to use its territory to attack Zairean
government troops, Zambian Foreign Minister Lawrence Shimba has
said.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia quoted him as saying here on Tuesday that
Zambia will continue to maintain the policy of non-interference
in internal affairs of other countries, adding that the Zambian
government is only concerned with its own security as it shares a
vast border area with Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"We are neutral and have nothing to do with the Zairean
conflict. Zaireans will handle their internal problems. We are
not going to accommodate any forces in this war. If the Katangese
intend to use our territory they must stop it," said Shimba.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports said the Katangese gendarmes, who had staged
foiled rebel wars in Zaire's southern Shaba Province in the 1970s
and the 1980s, have been regrouped from neighboring Angola and
Zambia to put up another fighting during the current Zairean
crisis.
</P>
<P>
At least 1,200 ex-Katangese soldiers have been sent to Zaire
to join the anti-government forces led by Laurent Kabila, said
the reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
