<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICC Experts Support China's Entry Into WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- China should join the World Trade
Organization as a developing country instead of as a developed
country, a number of renowned persons from the international
economic circles said here today.
</P>
<P>
Maria Livanos Cattaui, secretary general of the International
Chamber of Commerce (ICC), told Xinhua at the 32nd ICC global
meeting that though China is still a developing country, it is
growing in many fields and has become advanced in a few economic
areas in the world.
</P>
<P>
It is unfair to require China to join the WTO under the
conditions set for a developed country, international experts at
the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
A senior official from the ASEAN Chamber of Commerce and
Industry (ASEAN-CCI) said that the Association of Southeast Asia
Nations (ASEAN) will always support China's bid to join the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Keeping China out of the WTO has had negative impact on
economic development in Asia and the world, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Cattaui said that ICC, a first-class consultation organ of the
WTO, strongly supports China's bid to join the WTO and will use
its influence in connection with this issue.
</P>
<P>
A representative from the European Union said that the
short-sightedness of some countries that closed China off from the
WTO for political reasons is against the interests of the steady,
long-term development of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
All the experts said they are fully confident that China's bid
to join the WTO will be successful. They are here in Shanghai
to attend the 32nd global meeting of the ICC.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the prospect is bright for China to joint the
World Trade Organization," Arthur Dunkel, former director-general
of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Science Body Releases Report on National Conditions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The combination of labor resources and technology is an
advantage for China and has great potential, said the report,
adding that the country's weak points are in developing hi-tech
products and resource-consuming products.
</P>
<P>
China can no longer profit much from grain production in the
open international climate and with a shortage of arable land and
water. However, the report pointed out that China shows promise in
producing agro-products other than grain.
</P>
<P>
It said China should make full use of two resources -- land and
water, and two markets -- domestic and international, in addition
to diversified agro-resources and rural labor force to promote a
steady increase in grain production, develop high-value
agro-products and enhance international trade of agricultural
products.
</P>
<P>
One conclusion drawn in the report is that the necessary
solutions to China's agriculture and grain problems are pioneering
a development road that accords with China's national conditions,
modernizing its agriculture while staying in step with the
integration of the world economy, and steady growth in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The report maintains that bio-engineering projects are the best
way out for China's agriculture, and suggests that investment be
increased for bio-projects and basic research on gene technology
-- especially that which is closely related to grain production.
</P>
<P>
Improved strains of grain have played a special role in
agriculture. The report said that China should rely on everyday
technology to create many new strains in the short term, and use
highly-advanced technology to make breakthroughs in grain
development over the long run.
</P>
<P>
The report suggests that millions of farmers involved in
planting crops, cotton, fruit trees, flowers, and raising pigs and
fowl should be trained nationwide at rural vocational schools or
other training courses. The government should provide them with
small loans so that they can soon become the leading force in
agricultural production and scientific farming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
