<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Describes Ankara Visit as Productive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy has said that his talks with Turkish leaders were "very
friendly and productive."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a reception given by Israeli Ambassador to Turkey
Zvi Elpeleg Tuesday night, Levy, also deputy prime minister,
said that Israeli-Turkish relations will "go forward with grand
steps and further develop."
</P>
<P>
Levy, who arrived here Tuesday afternoon for a two-day
official visit, held talks with his Turkish counterpart Tansu
Ciller and met with President Suleyman Demirel and Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel Tuesday signed a memorandum of understanding
on land transportation between the two countries, which is
reported to serve as the basis of an agreement on broader
transportation cooperation in the future.
</P>
<P>
This was the third accord signed by Turkey and Israel
following a military training agreement and a free trade accord
which were inked last year.
</P>
<P>
The military training agreement signed by Ankara and Tel Aviv
in February 1996 triggered fear in the Middle East countries
that Turkey was aligning itself with Israel against Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
Levy will tour Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey,
this morning after his stay in Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
