<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese PLA Helps Farmers Shake off Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Both officers and men of the
People's Liberation Army have joined in the nationwide drive to
help the country's remaining 58 million to become well-to-do by
the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The PLA troops, stationed in the mountainous Enshi Prefecture,
central China's Hubei Province, initiated a successful practice to
aid the needy: one officer leading three militiamen to assist one
household in need.
</P>
<P>
Major Officer Zou Youxiang was moved when he first came to Zhou
Bukun's house in Jianshi county in 1994: a thatched house; two
girls, lean and haggard in rags, greedily looking at the celery
cooked in a pot over a muddy stand; a bench; and a bed with two
quilts for four family members. The whole property was no more
than 150 yuan-worth.
</P>
<P>
When spring came, the family would run out of provisions. Zhou
had to work for others in exchange for some grains, on which they
made a meagre living, together with edible wild herbs. His own
farm work was then held up as a result.
</P>
<P>
The major officer and three militiamen helped build a
stone-wood house, free of charge, for the family, and worked out
farming plans to ensure good harvests. The soldiers also helped
develop courtyard economy, planting thousands of trees around the
house and in the family's private mountain area.
</P>
<P>
The hostess said, smiling, that they produced more than 1,500
kg of grain last year, and for the first time in the past dozens
of years they slaughtered a pig of their own for the traditional
Spring Festival. One-thirtieth ha of tobacco land yielded over 500
yuan-worth last year, which served as pocket money.
</P>
<P>
Local stationed troops organized some 30,000 poverty relief
teams over the past 10 years, and helped 140,000 farmers of 60,000
households like Zhou Bukun to have adequate food, clothing and new
housing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Students Waiting for Better Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Only 10 percent of students who
are expected to graduate from famous universities in Shanghai this
summer have already found jobs. Most students are waiting for
better opportunities.
</P>
<P>
March and April are the traditional months for Chinese
university students to seek jobs, but the atmosphere is different
this year.
</P>
<P>
Educational authorities said that only 300 of the 2,800
graduates from Fudan University have signed contracts with their
employers. The rest are still hesitating between various
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the ratio of the units wanting to employ
college graduates to the graduates is 3.5 to one in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"It is now the seller's market," an official explained.
</P>
<P>
Since the country abolished the government-controlled job
assignment system for college graduates in early 1990s, there have
been mixed feelings among the students.
</P>
<P>
Some thought that there would be more job opportunities, some
were anxious about the future. However, as the economy continues
to prosper, the anxiety has been eased.
</P>
<P>
Many experts pointed out that the country is faced with a lack
of high-level expertise, but, at the same time, many unskilled
workers have been laid-off from state factories.
</P>
<P>
Survey shows that most graduates this year wish to work in
small companies, which are one of the most dynamic parts of the
Chinese economy, instead of rushing to big enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Some students are looking for job opportunities in government
departments which can provide them with good medical care and
stable salaries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
