<HEADLINE> African Nations Urged to Adopt Suitable Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Information Minister
Johnstone Makau has urged African countries to adopt culturally
friendly democracies to seek a long lasting peace in the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Kenya Times today quoted him as saying on
Tuesday that the recent political upheavals and turmoil facing
African countries have occurred "as a result of the West forcing
their ideas of democracy on us."
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "African countries should reassess their
democracies and agree on culturally friendly political ideologies
as a way of initiating a long lasting peace in the continent."
</P>
<P>
The minister was speaking when he received Algerian
Ambassador to Kenya Sid-Ali Ketrandji, who paid him a courtesy
call.
</P>
<P>
Makau noted that the Western countries have taken advantage of
many problems affecting the African people to enhance their
influence on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the crisis in eastern Zaire, he accused Western
countries of ignoring peace initiatives taken by African leaders
and only capitalizing on human sufferings brought about by
internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official urged African countries to set up trade
blocs to achieve economic independence and avoid over-reliance on
donor aid.
</P>
<P>
He said that Africa should stand to be counted as a continent
capable of running its affairs without outside interference.
</P>
</TEXT>
