<HEADLINE> Champions Sing Tao Face China Test in Viceroy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Newly-crowned Viceroy Cup
champions Sing Tao face an acid test when they take on Chinese
professional side Apollo Guangzhou in the Viceroy Challenge Cup
here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The confrontation between the two slated for Thursday evening
at the Mongkok Stadium promises one of the year's most exciting
matches as Apollo Guangzhou have made a flying start to China's
professional league season, staying undefeated in five games to
occupy a third place in the standings. They scored two wins and
three draws to throw down the challenge to leaders Dalian Wanda
and Shanghai Shenhua.
</P>
<P>
Sing Tao won their second Viceroy Cup by defeating another Hong
Kong senior side Happy Valley 7-6 on penalties here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sing Tao coach Chan Hung-ping said that his team will have a
tough task against Apollo Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
"Apollo Guangzhou have had a good run, staying unbeaten after
five matches. This is a very good result considering the depth
and strength of the Chinese League," said Chan.
</P>
<P>
"They will come to Hong Kong with their confidence lifted," he
added.
</P>
<P>
As for Apollo Guangzhou's coach Chen Yiming, the trophy for the
Challenge Cup match is also not something so easy.
</P>
<P>
"We have had five of our first-choice players left at home and
instead some newcomers are now on the team. We have to do our
utmost to play well and win," he said.
</P>
<P>
The organizers also announced here today the winners of the
Viceroy Cup's Best Defender, Best Attacker and Top Scorer's
awards. The winners were voted by members of the media covering
the annual tournament.
</P>
<P>
Sing Tao goalkeeper Iain Hesford, a 37-year-old from England,
was voted the event's Best Defender, Happy Valley's 20-year-old
striker Michael Midwood won the Best Attacker award while the
tournament's top scorer was given to Instant-Dict midfielder Ross
Greer, who scored three goals during the event.
</P>
<P>
And, as a curtain-raiser to the Viceroy Challenge Cup, Hong
Kong's All Star Soccer Association will play against the Writing
Machine Football Team, a team comprised of sports journalists from
the local media.  
</P>
</TEXT>
