<HEADLINE> Chinese, Spanish Scientists Surveying Caves in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- A team of Chinese and Spanish
scientists are now surveying a dozen caves on southwest China's
Yunnan-Guizhou Plateau.
</P>
<P>
The team arrived in Yunnan Province on March 18 before entering
Guizhou Province. They planned to stay there for 24 days.
</P>
<P>
The team consists of two karst specialists from the Chinese
Academy of Sciences and four Spanish environmental protection
experts and speleologists.
</P>
<P>
There is 1.37 million sq m of karst topography in China,
according to Zhang Shouyue, a member of the team. Some 240,900 sq
km of the area is in Yunnan and Guizhou, accounting for 17.58
percent of the total. The two provinces have become a research
base for the research and development of the cave resources.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that Spanish speleologists conduct field
a survey in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
