<HEADLINE> Uganda, Kenya Strive to End Tribal Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Kenya will hold a
peace meeting in Moroto, Uganda, on April 14-16 to settle
hostilities between tribesmen from Uganda's northern Karamoja
area and Kenya's Turkana region.
</P>
<P>
According to the local daily "the New Vision" today, the
hostilities were triggered by the scarcity of feeding resources
for their cattle during drought.
</P>
<P>
Among the issues to be discussed during the meeting are
security, famine, the plight of minority groups and the
development needs of the region.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Kenyan government officials, elders from the
cattle-keeping tribes of the region, donors and non-governmental
organizations, are expected to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Persistent border clashes between the tribesmen of the two
countries have caused grave concern among donors and governments
of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Five meetings have been held so far for the region. The latest
was in last November with encouraging results. enditem

