<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Science Body Releases Report on National Conditions (1) By Huang Yan and Li Xiguang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The National Conditions Analysis
and Research Group under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS)
today released the Fifth Report on the National Conditions, which
predicts that China will be able to feed itself in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The 300-page report, which is cautiously optimistic about the
food problem China will face in the 21st century, foresees that
China will be fully capable of providing food for its countrymen
by the middle of the next century and become one of the biggest
exporters of agricultural products in the world.
</P>
<P>
CAS, the Chinese government's top science and technology
advisor, in 1988 issued a warning about the country's grain
problem in its first report on national conditions, saying that
the problem of feeding the country's huge population will be the
top priority of the Chinese government in the coming decades.
</P>
<P>
And Lester Brown, president of the Washington-based Worldwatch
Institute, attracted international attention in the summer of 1994
by bluntly asking the question "Who will feed China?"
</P>
<P>
In the Fifth Report on the National Conditions, titled
"Agriculture and Development," CAS analyzed difficulties and
challenges that would confront China in feeding its people.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that China's grain production would be
seriously affected by high costs and low economic returns.
</P>
<P>
However, grain production is influenced by many favorable
factors, the report pointed out, citing examples of possible
increased financial support for agriculture as a result of rapidly
growing national strength, the advance of agro-science and
technology, increased capacity of agricultural production and
trade, and more market-oriented agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"China can be self-sufficient in the 21st century," the report
claimed, while at the same time emphasizing that the harvests of
last year and the year before were achieved due to the sharp
increase of grain prices which in turn brought more profits for
farmers.
</P>
<P>
"It would be very difficult to raise grain yield in this way in
the future," it noted.
</P>
<P>
Before China's population basically stops growing and the
country realizes industrialization in the mid-21st century, the
report noted,  agriculture will be a crucial and weak link that
restricts the growth of China's national economy for a fairly long
time to come.
</P>
<P>
China will have to deal with shortages of grain, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"It has become a very challenging task which requires decades
of effort by the government to meet the increasing demand for
grain of over one billion people and help hundreds of millions of
surplus rural laborers find jobs," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in the international market, China has no
advantages over other competitors in grain and oil
crops. Comparatively speaking, China is more competitive in
providing labor-intensive and some technology-intensive
agro-products.
</P>
<P>
"China should make the most of its advantage in rich labor
forces and natural resources and try profit-making agriculture and
intensive farming.
</P>
<P>
"There is a good possibility for China to become a highly
intensive farming country and a big exporter of agro-products in
the world," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in agriculture, China's status is between
very developed countries and developing countries. This position
allows China to make full use of its rich labor force that
developed countries don't have, and its relatively high technology
that isn't found in the developing countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0202 </DOCNO>
