<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Banks in Dire Straits Following </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi commercial banks, both
public and private, that invested in the capital market either in
buying shares or extending loans against securities, are facing
huge losses, said banking circle sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources reckon that different state-owned and private
commercial banks invested around tk 600 million (about 15 million
US dollars) against the securities of various listed companies.
</P>
<P>
In addition to direct investment, the nationalized commercial
banks (NCBs) had also extended huge credit against the securities,
a consolidated figure was not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
The central bank allowed the commercial banks to extend loans
of upto 60 percent of stock prices calculated on a six-month
average market value.
</P>
<P>
Both the operations, direct investment and granting of loans,
took place during the "bull and bubble" period. In the meantime
the capital market crashed. The all share price index shot up to
3,700 in the first week of November 1996 and fell to 1140.65 on
Tuesday last.
</P>
<P>
Due to the market crash, erosion of capital investment of the
commercial banks against the securities has been estimated at
about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the marker prices calculated in granting the
loans no longer exist as such the bank management would not be
able to realize their loan money by encashing the securities.
</P>
<P>
"It has not only created liquidity problems for the banks but
ultimately the volume of nonperforming loans will increase", said
an official of a commercial bank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
