<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Loans to Small, Medium Enterprises Increase in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Trade and Industry
Department today said the cumulative loans that the country's
small and medium enterprises (SME) obtained from commercial banks
soared to 4 billion US dollars from 1992 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
The department said in a report to President Fidel Ramos that
during the 46-year period from 1946 to 1992, the cumulative bank
loans funneled by commercial banks into the SME sector amounted to
only 608 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic increase showed the government's support for the
SMEs appears "to be paying off", the report said.
</P>
<P>
The President, who dubbed the SMEs as the "backbone of our
entrepreneurial drive," reported on the primordial importance his
administration is giving to the SMEs during the Fourth Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) Finance Ministers' Meeting
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The number of SMEs registered with the Securities and Exchange
Commission and the Board of Investments has been increasing since
1992, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the number of small enterprises increased by 26
percent over that of 1995, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
