<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D-8 Muslim Summit to be Held in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Turkey-sponsored D-8 Group,
which consists of eight Muslim countries, is expected to hold
its summit meeting in Turkey in June, the local newspaper Daily
News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan as
saying that about 50 cooperative projects would be discussed
during the summit.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, the enthusiastic initiator of the Muslim bloc, said
that the summit would set some important principles for the
organization in order to expand cooperation among the member
states.
</P>
<P>
He said that the planned projects involved 10 different
fields, such as trade, industry and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the principle that each state should
coordinate certain fields, Turkey will be responsible for the
coordination of cooperation in the sectors of industry and
health care.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said that they were only waiting for the approval of
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to finalize the scheme for the
summit.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Group consisting of Turkey, Iran, Egypt, Indonesia,
Pakistan, Nigeria, Malaysia and Bangladesh, was first proposed by
the Turkish prime minister and formed late last year.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim bloc, whose aim was to boost the multilateral
cooperation among the eight countries, held its first foreign
ministerial meeting in Turkey in 1996 and decided to establish
the general secretariat in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the D-8 Group has incited complaints
from the United States and European countries, which accused
Turkey of putting up a rival show agaisnt the G-7 group of the
developed countries in the West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
