<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Improves Teachers' Living Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- After crowding in two small rooms
for 20 years with a family of three generations, Geng moved to a
four-room apartment recently.
</P>
<P>
"It costed me 80,000 yuan, and now I can live comfortably,"
said Geng, who is an elementary school teacher in east China's
Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid development of the province's housing
construction and the steady growth of teachers' income, more
teachers like Geng have settled their housing problem in the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the province has invested some
1.2 billion yuan (about 150 million US dollars) in housing
construction for teachers in the past year, and a total of 2.09
million sq m.-floor-space of housing is under construction.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of 1.34 million sq m.-floor-space of
housing, the average living space of the province's teaching staff
has risen to 10.5 sq m. from 9.3 sq m. in early 1996, figures say,
and the present figure exceeds the province's average city and
town dwellers' living space by nearly two sq m.
</P>
<P>
The province has been increasing its financial support of the
housing construction for teachers, said an official with the
provincial government, adding that it earmarked a record 166
million yuan to the teachers' housing project last year, an
increase of 56 million yuan over 1995.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the province has taken measures to lower the cost of
the housing construction for teachers. Xuzhou City has brought
down the cost to 700 yuan per sq m.-floor space.
</P>
<P>
With the growth of income, teachers also have more money to
invest in housing. Statistics show that teachers contributed 700
million yuan, or 59 percent of the total that the province spent
in the teachers' housing project last year, while schools spent
220 million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
