<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Ministers of India, Pakistan Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Pakistan Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan today held an informal meeting with his
Indian counterpart I.K. Gujral and both sides decided to continue
the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan described his meeting with Gujral as "ice-breaking"
and expressed the hope that the Indo-Pak dialogue would continue
in the same spirit. Ayub, who was here to attend the Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM) foreign ministers' conference from April 7-8, later
left here for home.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Gujral said that his meeting with Mr. Ayub was held in a
warm and friendly atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Foreign secretaries of the two countries resumed their talks
here, stalled since January 1994, from March 28-31 and discussed
all outstanding issues between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both foreign ministers avoided reference to any particular
issue while answering questions, presumably to emphasize on the
decision to continue the dialogue without long intervals.
</P>
<P>
On April 6, the two foreign ministers had a round of informal
discussions at a dinner hosted by the High Commissioner of
Pakistan for Ayub Khan here. "My government believes in
step-by-step approach" in dealing with the ties of the two
countries, Ayub said on that occasion.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of his breakfast meeting with Gujral, the Pakistan
foreign minister called for closer trade relations with India,
saying that the two countries would benefit economically if the
tension between them eased.
</P>
<P>
Since division in 1947, the two countries have gone to war
three times due to disputes over Kashmir and other issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
