<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Achieve 5.5 Percent GDP Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 9 (Xinhua) --- Bangladesh may achieve a 5.5
percent GDP growth targeted for the current fiscal ending this
July as the socio-economic condition appears to have stabilized,
said a report of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report, the Bangladesh Bank said that Bangladesh
achieved a domestic product growth of 5.3 percent in 1995-96
fiscal, despite natural calamities, socio-economic unrest and
other non-economic factors.
</P>
<P>
The socio-economic unrest caused disruption in overall
production process, resulting in a slowdown in growth in the
manufacturing sector. Industrial growth dropped to 5.3 from 8.6
percent in the 1994-95 fiscal, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the construction sector also marked a sharp decline,
the central bank said. The sector grew 4 percent 1995-96 fiscal
against 7 percent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the power, gas, water and sanitary sectors dropped to
9.9 percent last year from 11.3 a year back. Cumulative growth in
other sectors also declined.
</P>
<P>
But a positive 3.5 percent growth in the agriculture sector in
1995-96 fiscal, up from a negative 1 percent the previous year,
contributed to the overall GDP growth rate in the year.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that increased dynamism would be infused into
the overall economic activities in 1996-97 fiscal because of
strengthening reform programs and the realistic and pragmatic
policies being followed in economic management, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It forecast that the agriculture growth might exceed 2 percent
and the service sector and industrial output are likely to
increase in the year, helping the country achieve the targeted
growth and keeping inflation at tolerable level.
</P>
<P>
The report, however, suggested that domestic credit and deficit
financing should be kept limited while reducing current
expenditure and mobilizing more domestic resources and attaching
priority to productive and employment-generating projects.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the banks faced a remarkable liquidity crisis due
to the dependence of the government on the banks caused by fall in
foreign assistance and food imports in public sector, and a huge
credit to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The total domestic credit rose by 20.4 percent in 1995-1996
fiscal compared to 17.6 percent a year back, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
