<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Horticulture Exports Lower Than </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's flower exports have so far
this season registered a 25-percent growth, lower than the predicted
30 percent increase, largely due to a severe European winter, the
Horticultural Promotion Council said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
''Our key marketing period coincided with a cold spell in Europe
that affected not only our customers, but also surface distribution,"
Chief Executive of the Council Stanley Heri said.
</P>
<P>
The second factor was that the volume of cut flowers in Zimbabwe
was down because of the continuous overcast weather, he said
commenting on the industry's export performance between july 1996 and
February 28 this year. The export season ends in June.
</P>
<P>
He said the symptoms from the market place for both flowers and
vegetables indicated severe competition from the African, Caribbean
and Pacific countries.
</P>
<P>
The competition meant Zimbabwe had to concentrate on quality of
both product and service, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, horticulture exports earned the country more than 100
million US Dollars. enditem

