<HEADLINE> Nuclear Powers Reiterate Support for Non-proliferation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- China, France, Russia,
Britain and the United States today reiterated their "strong and
continuing support" for the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty (NPT).
</P>
<P>
In a statement made at the first Preparatory Committee for the
2000 Review Conference of NPT, the five nuclear powers also said
they were determined to continue to implement all the provisions
of the treaty, including those of nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that since the May 1995 NPT Review and
Extension Conference, there have been very significant
developments in the area of nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) by
more than 140 states, including the five nuclear-weapon states
signed on the first day of its opening for signature on September
24, 1996, is a historic event," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
On the future efforts to support NPT, the five countries
reaffirmed their readiness for the immediate commencement and
early conclusion of the negotiations on the convention banning the
production of fissile material for nuclear weapons or other
nuclear explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free-zones
enhances global and regional peace and security, the five
countries pledged security assurance to the above-mentioned areas
in line with relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The five nuclear powers also said that they are committed to
cooperation in the field of nuclear energy for peaceful purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
