<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Clone Gene of Hereditary Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at Hunan Medical
University, funded by an American pharmaceutical company, have
cloned a gene that causes hereditary multiple exostosis.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time Chinese scientists succeed in cloning a
gene related to a hereditary disease. Earlier, American scientists
first cloned the gene linked to hereditary exostosis, a spur or
bony outgrowth from a bone or the root of a tooth.
</P>
<P>
A research group, led by Professor Deng Hanxiang, head of a
state key laboratory of medical genetics at the university and
Professor Xia Jiahui, director of the Academic Committee, cloned
the gene, EXT2, last August, after six years of efforts.
</P>
<P>
Backed by China's Public Health Ministry, Smithkline Beecham
Co. of the United States, one of the four largest pharmaceutical
companies in the world, began to fund the laboratory in February,
1996. The company provided 2.36 million US dollars to the lab for
the first stage of research, which focused on human gene studies.
</P>
<P>
Scientists across the world began the studies of human gene
cloning in the early 1980s, duplicating a gene and interpreting
its codes.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say there are about 50,000 to 100,000 different
human genes. Among more than 3,000 human genes that cause
hereditary diseases, over 260 have been cloned by the scientists
around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
