<HEADLINE> Most Social Sciences Researchers in Tibet Are Tibetans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The majority of social sciences
researchers in the Social Sciences Academy of the Tibet Autonomous
Region are Tibetans, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from Han ethnic group and other ethnic minorities
just account for five percent of the 127 scholars in the academy,
the top research institute in the region.
</P>
<P>
Among them 31 are research fellows and associate research
fellows.
</P>
<P>
Cering, president of the academy, said that Tibetan scholars
are mainly engaged in five fields, namely the studies of ethnic
groups, religion, contemporary Tibet, the rural economy, and
economic strategy.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than 50 Tibetan researchers from the academy
have visited 20 countries and regions, including the United
States, and many foreign scholars have carried out programs at the
academy.
</P>
<P>
Last year the academy received 30 scholars from Norway,
Germany, Japan, France and Austria. 
</P>
