<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Lowers Tariffs on Farm Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government has
decided to lower tariffs on farm imports as part of the country's
efforts to join the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The decision, made on Monday, would bring down the tariffs to
meet EU standards, said Florea Tuiu, a director with the official
Rompress news agency's economic desk, today.
</P>
<P>
With a 60 percent ceiling on all foreign farm produce except
alcohol, beverage, tobacco and cigarette, the revised import
tariffs will average no more than 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, under the new system, the tariff on imported pork
will drop from 263 to 50 percent, and that on chicken meat will
also go down from 143 to between 50 and 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, some critics here have been against the move, alleging
that the lower tariffs may harm Romania's agricultural sector as
they allow foreign goods to flock into the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Romanian government early this
month deregulated the prices for wheat, pork, chicken meat and
milk by eliminating subsidies for these farm produce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
