<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Economy Expected to Grow Faster in Coming Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth in New Zealand
is expected to be around 3 percent a year during the next three
years, with the government spending the dynamo in the coming two
years, the National Bank forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The bank's predictions for April issued today, suggest the
economy is past the trough in the present business cycle. The
combination of high interest rates and a high NZ dollar slowed the
economy in the second half of 1996, with exporters bearing the
brunt.
</P>
<P>
But the recovery in the coming year could be an "unhappy" one,
the bank says. Production will still grow, but job growth will
slow, the jobless rate will rise and the export sector will
struggle.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit, the difference between what New
Zealand earns and spends overseas, will grow toward 6 percent of
the gross domestic product, the bank forecasts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
