<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Manufacture Production Begins to Pick Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Manufactured exports returned
to growth in the December quarter last year after 15 months of
weakening, making up for slower domestic sales, the New Zealand
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a Westpac Trust's analysis of manufacturing
industries as saying manufactured exports grew 0.4 percent during
the December period, up from minus 2.8 percent and minus 2.3
percent in the preceding quarters.
</P>
<P>
"While this is a very slow rate of growth, export volumes for
the December quarter moved above those for the previous peak in
the June 1995 quarter for the first time."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, domestic sales growth was down to 0.9
percent in the December quarter, from 1.2 percent in the previous
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The strong NZ dollar and tariff reduction hit knitting mills,
clothing, leather, footwear and motor vehicle assembly. Export
markets remain weak for fish and pulp and paper, the report said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
