<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto, Cohen Agree on Reducing Okinawa Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen agreed
today to help reduce Okinawa's heavy burden arising from the
U.S. military presence in Japan.
</P>
<P>
They reached the agreement during an hour-long breakfast
meeting at the Japanese prime minister's official residence, Kyodo
News Service quoted a senior foreign ministry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the two leaders failed to come up with new specific
measures to alleviate the burden on Okinawa. They only reaffirmed
that the two countries planned to streamline U.S. military
facilities and return to local landowners some space in Okinawa
occupied by the U.S. facilities under a bilateral agreement
reached last year.
</P>
<P>
Cohen reiterated that the United States will maintain its
current 100,000-strong troops in the Asia-Pacific region, and it
will consult with Japan over any military action if major changes
occur in the future.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told Cohen that Japan will not seek to reduce the
bulk of U.S. troops for the time being.
</P>
<P>
The United States currently maintains a 100,000-strong force in
forward deployment in East Asia, including 47,000 in Japan, of
which, about 27,000 are stationed in Okinawa, the country's
southernmost island prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa, which accounts for less than one percent of Japan's
total land area, is also home to some 75 percent of all land used
by the U.S. military in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Okinawa prefectural government and local residents have
opposed the U.S. military presence there, calling for withdrawal
of U.S. troops from the prefecture by 2015.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Hashimoto and Cohen also reached an
agreement that the two countries will issue an interim report
reviewing the 1978 Guidelines for Japan-U.S. defense cooperation
sometime after mid-May, foreign ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen will leave for South Korea this afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
