<HEADLINE> Ousted Police Chief in Nepal Challenges His Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 9 (Xinhua) -- An ousted police chief in Nepal
has submitted a petition to the Supreme Court against the
government's decision to remove him from the post of Inspector
General of Police (IGP) last week, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
Ex-IGP Ackyut Krishna Kharel said Tuesday after registering his
petition in the Court that he wanted to seek justice and the
dignity of the police through his move.
</P>
<P>
The government, which came to power in early March, decided
last week to transfer Kharel from the job of police chief to the
head of the National Investigation Department and appoint one of
his assistants as IGP.
</P>
<P>
Kharel reportedly claimed in his petition that the government
had no legal authority to make such a transfer.
</P>
<P>
Kharel's petition also demanded the Court to issue an interim
order directing the defendants including the cabinet, the home
minister and the newly appointed IGP not to prevent him carrying
out his duties as the IGP until the case is settled.
</P>
<P>
The Court's hearing on the case is expected to begin from
today. 
