<HEADLINE> NATO Expansion is Historic Mistake: Belarus President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Belarus President Alexander
Lukashenko said in Minsk today that NATO's expansion towards
central and eastern European countries is a historic mistake.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko made the statement at an international symposium,
which centered on building a nuclear-free zone in central and
eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko said it was strange that Western countries welcomed
the withdrawal of nuclear weapons from Belarus on the one hand
while stalling on the issue of building nuclear-free zones.
</P>
<P>
A security mechanism dominated by a few countries won't work in
the long run, Lukashenko added.
</P>
<P>
The Belarus president first proposed the establishment of a
nuclear-free zone in central and eastern Europe on July 3 last year.
</P>
<P>
He said in his speech today that there was no reason to hinder
the building of such a zone in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said at
the same workshop that an international agreement should be signed
in order to build a nuclear-free zone in central Europe.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia and Ukraine support the Belarus
initiative on the establishment of a nuclear-free zone. 
</P>
