<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombia is projected to produce and
consume 500 million cubic feet of natural gas per day this year,
Colombia's state-owned petroleum company said.
</P>
<P>
The largest consumers are the thermoelectrical sector with
186.5 million cubic feet per day, the petroleum sector with 133
million, the industrial sector with 106.5 million and the domestic
sector with 42.7 million.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's cigarette sales dropped 20 percent
during the first quarter of this year compared with the same
period of 1996, said Martin Murphy Sahores, the general manager of
Venezuela's Tabacalera Nacional.
</P>
<P>
Despite the decrease, the market could begin to recover in June
and finally fulfill the projection for an increase at the end of
the year as a result of the higher purchasing power stemmed from
the recent agreements reached by the government, the private
business and the labor, the manager said.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The consumption of public services in Argentina
increased 12.3 percent in February compared with the same period
of 1996, said the National Institute of Statistics and Census.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications sector saw the highest growth with 30.7
percent, followed by the sectors of energy and motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's exports of live sheep, mutton and their
by-products during the 1996-97 slaughter season totaled 17,286,388
U.S. dollars, a 122.9 percent rise compared with the previous
season.
</P>
<P>
Of all the related categories, the by-products increased by
353.8 percent, rising from 245,428 dollars in the previous season
to 1,113,778 dollars in the present one.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- A second methanol plant has started to operate in
Cabo Negro, of southern Chile.
</P>
<P>
The new plant, built with an investment of 280 million dollars,
will produce 900,000 metric tons of methanol per year and raise
Chile's methanol output to 1.7 million metric tons in 1997.
</P>
<P>
With its operation and that of a third plant in 1999, Cabo
Negro will be the world's biggest methanol center with a combined
annual capacity of producing 2.7 million metric tons of methanol.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Central American countries will need at least 7.557
billion dollars over the next nine years to develop its electrical
power sector, said a report by the United Nations Economic
Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean (CEPAL).
</P>
<P>
In the Central American region, 7.557 billion dollars will be
needed for the 1996-2005 period to satisfy the demand for
electrical power that will grow an average of 6.2 percent, or
1,570 gigawatts per year, the CEPAL said.
</P>
<P>
The installed electrical capacity now in Central American
countries is 5,207 megawatts, of which 53 percent is generated by
hydroelectrical plants, 42 percent by thermoelectrical plants and
5 percent by geothermal plants.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) will
grant a 420 million dollars loan for the construction of a section
of a subway line in Sao Paulo, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
IDB President Enrique Iglesias and Sao Paulo Governor Mario
Covas signed a financing agreement here on April 6.
</P>
<P>
The Sao Paulo Metropolitan Train company will carry out the
improvement and expansion work of the subway line.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Spanish government will grant Nicaragua 250
million dollars in financial aid, said Nicaragua's Foreign Aid
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The aid was negotiated during a meeting in Spain between Luis
Espinoza, secretary general of Spain's International Aid Agency
and Nicaraguan Foreign Aid Minister David Robleto.
</P>
<P>
The Money will be used in the sectors of health, education and
tourism.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Panamanian government has registered at
least 354 million dollars of internal debt in the past 15 months,
said the National Bank of Panama (BNP).
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the BNP lent 177.3 million dollars to diverse public
institutions.
</P>
<P>
So far in 1997, the BNP has already been authorized to lend the
Institute of Communications 30 million dollars and 5 million
dollars to the Panama Canal Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
