<HEADLINE> Italy, Russia Say NATO-Russia Accord Important for Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The accord between the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) and Russia is important to the
architecture of future European security, Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini and visiting Russian First Deputy Foreign Minister
Alexander Avdeyev said today.
</P>
<P>
Dini and Avdeyev hoped that the accord could be made before the
NATO summit in Madrid this July.
</P>
<P>
Russia, though still strongly opposed to NATO's eastward
expansion, dropped the demand at the Russia-U.S. Helsinki summit
that a NATO-Russia document governing the two sides' future
relationship be a legally binding one.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his U.S. counterpart Bill
Clinton, who agreed on the principle of the accord, may sign it in
Paris as early as May 5, Itar-Tass news agency reported last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Dini and Avdeyev also expressed interest in deepening dialogues
between Rome and Moscow and announced the meeting of a joint
economic committee in Moscow on May 23.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also said that Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov will visit Rome in the next few weeks, while
President Yeltsin is planning a visit to Italy this fall. 
</P>
