<HEADLINE> Italy Backs Poland's Bid to Join NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Italy reiterated today its support
for Poland's bid to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) after two days of talks cleared a misunderstanding between
Rome and Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
The Poles reacted negatively after Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said in his visit to Moscow in February that NATO
enlargement must take place with Russia's consensus and "not
against its will."
</P>
<P>
Visiting Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski said
misunderstanding about Italy's views on Poland's bid for NATO had
been cleared up after his talks with Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi.
</P>
<P>
"Prodi's words, both today in Rome as well as in Warsaw, were
clear and unequivocal and leave no doubt of Italy's backing for
our entry in NATO and in the European Union," said the president.
</P>
<P>
Confirming Kwasniewski's remarks, Prodi said he was convinced
there would be no Russian veto on Poland's campaign to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
Russia, though still opposed to NATO's eastward expansion to
accept some of its former bloc allies, at the Helsinki summit
dropped demands for a deal mapping out relations with NATO be
legally binding.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has also agreed that an agreement with the military
alliance will be concluded before the NATO Madrid summit in July,
when the alliance is expected to announce who -- most likely
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic -- will be invited.
</P>
<P>
In a subtle signal of some possible leftovers from the recent
tension between Warsaw and Rome, Kwasniewski said "the hesitant
Italian politicians who go to Moscow should make a stop in Warsaw
to see the results Poland has obtained."
</P>
<P>
"It is not that Italians are hesitant," Prodi replied, "We are
talking about give and take and in any case the government's
position is consistent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
