<HEADLINE> Brazil to Increase Paper Production in 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Brazil will invest 13 billion
U.S. dollars in its paper sector in 10 years in a bid to meet the
growing domestic demand and increase paper export.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here today by Osmar Elias Zogbi, president
of the Brazilian Association of Pulp and Paper Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a session of the International Conference of the
Pulp and Paper Industry being held in Rio de Janeiro, Zogbi said
that Brazil's domestic paper consumption will increase by five
percent by the year 2000 and by six percent between 2001 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, one of the main producers of pulp and paper in the
world, earns two billion dollars a year through its paper export.
And the paper sector itself is able to earn more than seven
billion dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
If its paper manufacturing capacity remained at the current
level, Brazil would turn into a paper importer, Zogbi warned.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to allocate more funds to the paper sector
and to introduce an appropriate policy which would sharpen the
competitive edge of Brazil's paper sector in world markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
