<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism in Zhejiang Booming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Over 27,800 overseas tourists
visited coastal Zhejiang Province in January, 20 percent more than
the first month of 1996.
</P>
<P>
That month, the province, famous for the West Lake in Hangzhou
and historical sites such as Shaoxing and Ningbo, received 466,900
Chinese travelers, a jump of 98 percent.
</P>
<P>
Provincial authorities estimate visits by overseas and
domestic tourists will grow by seven and four percent respectively
this year. Tourism earnings from both overseas and domestic
sources are expected to increase eight percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Zhejiang in east China played host to 729,000 overseas
tourists and 37.73 million domestic tourists, up 8.4 percent and
5.1 percent respectively from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The province last year earned 292 million US dollars from
overseas tourism, up 23.7 percent and 23.2 billion yuan (2.795
billion US dollars) from domestic tourism. Its total tourism
earnings of the year accounted for 6.2 percent of its GDP.
</P>
<P>
Under a long-term plan, the province expects to receive 860,000
overseas tourists by the year 2000, and 1.4 to 1.6 million
overseas tourists by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
