<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Methane Gas Replaces Wood in Rural Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua)-- Methane gas is replacing wood as a
major energy source in Lijiang Naxi Autonomous County, of
southwestern China's Yunnan Province, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The methane is derived from decayed animal and human excrement
that was piped from latrines and pigsties into the special pits.
</P>
<P>
Plastic pipelines then bring the methane gas from the pits to
local houses.
</P>
<P>
"One third of Lijiang's people will use methane gas pits by the
end of 2000, when 5,000 pits will be operating," according to Mu
Zuoyi, deputy secretary of the Communist Party Committee of the
Lijiang Agriculture Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The county government will offer 200 yuan (24 US dollars) to
subsidize each family for the installation, Mu said.
</P>
<P>
It will help significantly to protect the environment and the
forests, said Zhang Yunping, deputy head of the county.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all the households in the county have upgraded their
stoves to burn less firewood. The government has spent several
million yuan on the project.
</P>
<P>
As a side benefit, sanitation in toilets and pigsties has been
dramatically improved.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
