<HEADLINE> City of Iron, Steel Develops Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Anshan, known as a "capital of
iron and steel", has sprung up as a new tourist city drawing
overseas investors and tourists.
</P>
<P>
An industrial base built in the early 1950s, Anshan in
northeast China's Liaoning Province made important contributions
to the country's economic construction, but tapping the rich
tourism resources has been made possible only in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and 1995, the city earmarked about 1.2 billion
yuan (144.5 million US dollars) for tourism development, twenty
times the total spent during the previous decade.
</P>
<P>
The investment has resulted in the construction of five scenic
areas, 21 hotels catering to overseas tourists, 100 holiday
resorts, and ten travel agencies.
</P>
<P>
Over 30 million yuan of the investment was put into building or
renovating the city's "trump card" tourist spots, including the
"Tang Emperor Hot Spring" -- the site where Emperor Taizong of
the Tang Dynasty (608-907) took baths; the "Longquan Villa" of
Zhang Zuolin, a north China warlord and father of General Zhang
Xueliang; and "Longgong Hot Spring" of Pu Yi, last emperor of the
Qing Dynasty (1644-1911). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
