<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Dollar Sends Baht to 7 And Half Years' Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand said today
that the sharp drop of the Thai baht against the U.S. dollar was
due to the strength of the dollar rather than any weakness in the
Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
The baht on Tuesday fell to its lowest level against the U.S.
dollar in seven and a half years, dropping 12 satang from Friday,
the last trading day (with Monday being a public holiday and the
foreign exchange market closed), to the 26.06 baht, the biggest
single-day change on record.
</P>
<P>
Trading was light in a range of 26.092 to 26.095, slightly
above the bandwidth of the 26.06 baht official midrate, which was
the lowest since September 13, 1989.
</P>
<P>
Tanasak Chantarovas, deputy director of the central bank's
banking department, said the depreciation of the baht against the
dollar is merely a consequence of the dollar appreciating against
the Japanese yen and the Deutschmark in the global market.
</P>
<P>
Tanasak said the central bank believes the current round of
dollar appreciation is temporary and that the bank will keep the
interbank rate high to deter speculators.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts and some government officials have been
calling for the central bank to change the makeup of its basket of
currencies. They say heavier weighting of the yen and the
Deutschmark would lessen dependence on high domestic interest
rates to defend the baht when the dollar climbs.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand said the rate had been set based on its
standard basket of currencies, in which the U.S. dollar is
believed to account for at least 80 percent of the basket.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers say they expect movement in the
foreign-exchange market to be quieter than in February, when
devaluation rumors were flying.
</P>
<P>
Investors now appear to have been persuaded by repeated Bank of
Thailand declarations that the baht would not be devalued in the
near term.
</P>
<P>
They say the major factor driving the dollar up against the yen
was a statement by U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin that
Washington would not use foreign-exchange mechanisms as a tool in
managing international trade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
