<HEADLINE> Italian Senate Approves Government Motion on Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Senate passed today a
government resolution to send Italian soldiers with an
international force to crisis-ridden Albania.
</P>
<P>
The motion was approved with a vote of 154 in favor, 119
opposed and three abstaining.
</P>
<P>
But the government is expected to face on Wednesday a tougher
test in the Chambers of Deputies, or the lower house of
parliament, where it lacks a majority without the backing of far
left Communist Refoundation.
</P>
<P>
Motions on Albania put forward by the center-right, the
Northern League, and Communist Refoundation were all voted down.
</P>
<P>
The Senate also vetoed, by a show of hands vote, a center-right
motion concerning funding for the mission to Albania, where the
failure of get-rich-quick investment schemes prompted widespread
violence and unrest in the past month.
</P>
<P>
Italy, the destination for about 13,000 Albanian refugees
fleeing from the crisis, would lead for the first time such an
international military mission since World War II.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to contribute 2,500 troops to the United
Nations-approved mission, together with 1,000 from France, 700
from Greece, 500 from Turkey, 400 from Romania and 300 from Spain.
</P>
<P>
Denmark and Austria are also reportedly considering joining the
multinational force to be deployed later this week to protect aid
transportation to the tiny Balkan nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
