<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Financial Sector's Creditworthiness Still at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The creditworthiness of Thai
financial institutions could come under further downward pressure,
according to the Rating Agency Standard and Poor's.
</P>
<P>
The sharp slowdown in the Thai economy since last year has
brought to the fore the pitfalls of excessive bank lending,
particularly to the property market.
</P>
<P>
In mid-March, Standard and Poor's affirmed Thailand's "A"
long-term and "A-1" short-term foreign currency ratings. The
outlook on the long-term rating remains stable.
</P>
<P>
But at the same time, the agency downgraded Thai Farmers' Bank
Plc and Siam Commercial Bank Plc, affirmed the ratings of Bangkok
Bank Plc and Bank of Asia Plc, and placed two others on its
"creditwatch" with negative implications: Bank of Ayudhya Plc and
Industrial Finance Corporation of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The rating outlooks for Thai Farmers, Siam Commercial, Bangkok
Bank and Bank of Asia were revised to negative.
</P>
<P>
Standard and Poor's said in its edition of credit week,
released today, that tight monetary policies and the property
slump, combined with lax regulations, declining margins and rising
corporate and household debt, have weakened loan portfolios and
along with them, the average credit quality of the financial
sector.
</P>
<P>
It said the government's commitment to a stable baht exchange
rate means interest rates are likely to remain high throughout
1997.
</P>
<P>
In addition, general operating conditions will remain
difficult. As a result, the extent of financial sector stress is
expected to be more significant and prolonged than currently
foreseen by the regulators and financial institutions. But it is
unlikely to reach crisis proportions, said the agency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
