<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales in Italy Up 4.6 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in Italy rose by 4.6
percent in 1996 despite a one percent downturn last December over
the same period in 1995, the country's National Statistics
Institute (ISTAT) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The rise should be mainly attributed to the performance of
discount stores, which saw a 12.4 percent increase for the whole
year and 2.8 percent for December, ISTAT said.
</P>
<P>
However, sales through large department stores fell by 5.4
percent in 1996, while medium-size stores with 10 to 19 employees
recorded a virtually flat performance, up by a slender 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Food stores witnessed the sharpest increase of 7.3 percent last
year, followed by perfume and cosmetics stores with 5.4 percent,
book stores with 1.7 percent and clothing and shoe stores with 0.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Declines were seen in photo and optical equipment shops with
2.3 percent, furniture stores 0.9 percent and stores selling
household items 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
ISTAT's figure for December alone, signaling Christmas
shopping, showed a 4.2 percent increase for stores selling
household items and hardware, 1.4 percent for perfume shops and
0.4 percent for food stores.
</P>
<P>
Sales through other stores registered decreases during the
shopping season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
