<HEADLINE> CMB Expands Overseas Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- China Merchants Bank (CMB), the
country's first commercial bank, plans to establish more overseas
representative offices in the next five years, "China Daily"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
North America, Western Europe and Southeast Asia will be the
main targets of the overseas expansion move, said CMB president
Wang Shizhen.
</P>
<P>
The bank is to upgrade its Hong Kong representative office into
a full branch to further promote its role in attracting foreign
capital to the Chinese mainland, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen-based bank, celebrating its 10th anniversary
yesterday, is now owned by 93 shareholders including China
Merchants Group Co. and China Ocean Shipping Corp.
</P>
<P>
CMB has enjoyed fast business growth in the last decade,
Wang said, noting that the bank's fixed assets surpassed 100
billion yuan (12.1 billion US dollars) by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The bank has established business relations with 655 banks in
33 nations and regions around the world, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It has attracted 200 million US dollar-worth of overseas
capital by issuing billions of floating-interest fixed deposit in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The bank has set up 10 branches in large Chinese cities,
including Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Wuhan, Chengdu, and
Nanjing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
