<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (11-12) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (11-12) in
a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: How is the Hong Kong SAR different from the special
economic zones in the mainland?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The Hong Kong SAR is a local administrative region
directly under the central government. It enjoys executive and
legislative powers and independent judicial power, including that
of final adjudication.
</P>
<P>
Special economic zones in the mainland, by comparison, enjoy
only preferential economic policies but not a high degree of
autonomy. While in the Hong Kong SAR the capitalist system will
remain unchanged for 50 years, special economic zones in the
mainland will continue to practice the socialist system.
</P>
<P>
Question: What are the differences between the government of
the Hong Kong SAR and the British Hong Kong government?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Differences between the two governments are
fundamental. The British Hong Kong government before July 1, 1997
is a government through which Britain imposes its colonial rule
over Hong Kong. The Hong Kong SAR government after July 1, 1997
will be the government of a special administrative region directly
under the central government after China resumes its exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The head of the British Hong Kong government is the governor
appointed by Britain. It is, therefore, the rule of Hong Kong by
the British. Whereas the Hong Kong SAR government will be formed
through local elections or consultations, and the chief executive
of the Hong Kong SAR will be appointed by the central
government. It is the rule of Hong Kong by Hong Kongers.
</P>
<P>
The British Hong Kong government implements royal instructions
from London, whereas the Hong Kong SAR government will implement
the Basic Law as the fundamental legal code.
</P>
<P>
Governors of Hong Kong have been accountable to the British
Crown and the British government, whereas the chief executive of
the Hong Kong SAR will be accountable to the central government of
China and the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
The governor of Hong Kong has been appointed by the British
Queen, and Hong Kong people have no right of supervision over
him.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, if the chief executive of the Hong Kong SAR is
accused of serious law violations or serious dereliction of duty,
the legislature of the Hong Kong SAR may start impeachment
proceedings against him and report to the central government for
decision.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
