<HEADLINE> Canada to Provide Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced today that it will
provide 2.6 million U.S. dollars' worth of food aid to victims of
flooding and famine in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK).
</P>
<P>
This decision was made in response to a United Nations appeal
for the people of DPRK, and the food distribution will be
coordinated by the World Food Program, according to the Canadian
International Development Agency (CIDA).
</P>
<P>
"A famine in North Korea has created enormous suffering," said
Canadian Minister for International Cooperation Don Boudria.
</P>
<P>
"It is a priority for Canada's aid program, and an urgent moral
responsibility to respond," Boudria added.
</P>
<P>
United Nations officials concluded after a recent tour of the
DPRK that 1.8 million metric tons of food were required to meet
the needs of the country's 24 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
