<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Chinese Province Lightens Farmers' Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has taken effective measures to lighten farmers'
financial burdens, and kept the ratio of miscellaneous charges
under five percent of farmers' net income.
</P>
<P>
The province has reduced more than 300 million yuan of illicit
fees on farmers over the past four years, abiding by the
percentage designated by the State Council, China's highest
governing body, said officials with the Provincial Agriculture
Department.
</P>
<P>
Trimming its payrolls, Tieling County has cut out 2,300
redundant personnel at the township and village level in the past
three years, saving farmers' 1.26 million yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
Entertainment allowances were another heavy burden on
farmers. The provincial government set a maximum limit. Beining
City even stopped running village canteens, and officials at the
township and village level are not allowed to eat in
restaurants. As a result, the city's entertainment expenses in
rural areas plummeted last year to only six percent that of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Also in the city, some leaders of one village apportioned
among villagers one million-yuan interest on loans for village
enterprises. They lost their jobs when an inspection
team discovered their malpractice.
</P>
<P>
The province defines explicitly that money turned over to
township governments by farmers is subject to unified management,
and may be incorporated into township revenues to prevent such
money from being misappropriated. To date, the stipulation has
been carried out in 80 percent of the townships of the province.
</P>
<P>
A budget and settlement system was introduced to reduce the
farmers' burdens. A card of detailed list of reasonable charges is
presented to each family. Farmers can refuse to pay for extra
fees. More than 90 percent of farmers now hold this card.
</P>
<P>
Efforts of this kind have encouraged farmers to invest more
in agricultural production. And their initiative contributed
greatly to the province's growing grain output, which exceeded
more than 16 billion kilograms last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
