<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Develops Tourism Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- China's youngest municipality of
Chongqing plans to achieve an annual growth rate of eight to ten
percent in the city's tourism sector in the coming five years.
</P>
<P>
This means that by the year of 2000, Chongqing will receive
350,000 overseas tourists and earn 150 million U.S. dollars a year
from related services, according to Zou Jiping, deputy director of
Chongqing Municipal Tourism Administration.
</P>
<P>
She went on to say that booming tourism will help create
employment opportunities for 200,000 people who have to be
resettled because of the on-going construction of a gigantic water
control dam at the Three Gorges on the middle reaches of the
Yangtze River. The three Gorges Area falls right under the
jurisdiction of Chongqing Municipality directly under the central
government.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, located on the juncture of Yangtze and Jialing
rivers, is a city built on a range of hills and is home to many
important historical and cultural relics. It is also well known
for a host of places associated with famous Chinese figures and
events, and its unique cuisine.
</P>
<P>
However, the city, well-known for its heavy fog, has long been
treated by tourists as a stepping stone on their tours to the
Three Gorges area, and many tourists go directly to cruisers after
their planes land, without spending one night in Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy director, the city has been developing
a number of quality tourism programs to attract more domestic and
overseas tourists and make them want to stay longer in Chongqing
and the Three Gorges Dam area.
</P>
<P>
The city was visited by 150,000 overseas tourists last year, an
increase of 25 percent over the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
