<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Citic to Invest in Shanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- China's International Trust and
Investment Corp (Citic) will begin building a 100 million
US dollar-worth project in landlocked Shanxi Province next year,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with a contract signed in Beijing yesterday, a
new joint venture, the Shanxi International Casting Co. Ltd., will
be established to manufacture engine-related castings for medium
and heavy-duty diesel engines.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project, involving investment of
44.3 million US dollars, will upgrade an existing factory and
produce 45,000 tons of castings a year.
</P>
<P>
The total annual production capacity of the project is expected
to reach 85,000 tons of castings, after the second phase
requiring 54.5 million US dollars is completed by 2003.
</P>
<P>
The project is scheduled to kick off in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Southwest China's Guangxi Yuchai Machinery Company Ltd, one of
the largest engine producers in the country, is expected to become
the main domestic customer, and about 40 percent of the output
will be exported.
</P>
<P>
The project is one that carries out the central government's
policy of encouraging more investment in central and western
regions, where it will take advantage of abundant raw materials in
Shanxi province.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi, located southwest of Beijing, has been designated as a
key economic zone in China due to its plentiful resources
including coal and pig iron, its qualified labor force and its low
cost untilities.
</P>
<P>
Citic is a main official investment arm under the State Council
directly, whose total capital has reached 191.5 billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Boosts Service Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, upgraded last month
to municipality status, is devoting major efforts to develop the
service trade.
</P>
<P>
An old industrial base, Chongqing had previously stressed
industry and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Service industry developed rapidly since the 1990s. The
percentage of the service trade in the city's Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) grew from 10 percent to 33 percent. But, that is
much lower than the average rate of 45 percent in three other
municipalities -- Beijing, Tianjin, and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The government of Chongqing pledges it will raise the ratio of
service trade in the city's GDP to 40 percent by the year 2000 and
to 52 percent by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Commerce, finance, tourism, communications and
telecommunications, real estate, and information industries have
been listed on top of the agenda for future development.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing will build an international trade center, set up a
financial zone, open tourist routes at the Three Gorges of the
Yangtze River, Wujiang Canyon, and Wuling Mountain, and build a
communication network which combines air, water, and highway
traffic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cellular Telephone Services to Be Privatized in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Renato Guerreiro, executive
secretary of Brazil's Telecommunications Ministry, announced that
the "B" band of Brazil's cellular telephone services will be
privatized at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The sale of the B band of cellular telephone services to
private capital will be the first step in the privatization of
Brazil's telecommunications sector, the official was quoted as
saying by the local press today.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen domestic and foreign consortiums participated in the
public auction held Tuesday by the Brazilian Telecommunications
Ministry for the installation and operation of cellular telephone
services at the above-mentioned frequency.
</P>
<P>
The authorities will announce who won the bid within 60 days.
The government will receive 6 billion U.S. dollars from the
privatization of this cellular telephone service.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 95 percent of the services offered by Brazil's
telecommunications sector belongs to the state and 3 million
Brazilians use cellular telephone services.
</P>
<P>
According to Telecommunications Minister Sergio Motta, the
conventional telephone sector will also be privatized within the
next two or three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
