<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine-man Tenerife Beat Schalke 1-0 at Uefa Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Spain's Tenerife hung on for a 1-0
win over Schalke of Germany despite conceding a penalty and being
reduced to nine men in an UEFA Cup semi-final first leg match in
Tenerife on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tenerife scored the winning goal through a fifth-minute penalty
but lost their way when Angel Vivar Dorado was sent off early in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish side survived a penalty miss after goalkeeper
Marcelo Ojeda was dismissed 15 minutes from the end.
</P>
<P>
The Spaniards controlled the opening phase of the match and
were rewarded quickly when Juanele Castanos broke down the right
and was brought down in the area by Schalke captain Olaf Thon.
</P>
<P>
The German eleven started strongly after the break, but it was
Tenerife's Felipe who came closest to scoring in the early
minutes, curling wide a shot after the Spaniards regained the
ball after a mistake by Thon.
</P>
<P>
But ten minutes into the second half the game changed shape
radically when Angel Vivar Dorado was sent off for elbowing
Radoslav Latal in retaliation for a heavy challenge.
</P>
<P>
From then on Tenerife lived dangerously as Schalke's Marc
Wilmots hit the bar with a header and Ingo Anderbruegge forced two
fine saves out of Ojeda.
</P>
<P>
Ojeda's last-ditch challenge earned him a red card and his
place was taken by substitute goalkeeper Bengt Andersson.
</P>
<P>
But Andersson was called on to make a series of saves in a
frantic last 15 minutes as Schalke tried to level the score.
</P>
<P>
Schalke will play the second leg game without suspended Andreas
Mueller but Tenerife will be without Ojeda, Vivar Dorado and
Antonio Robaiana, who was sent off in their last tie.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
