<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Canada Shipping Agreement Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- China and Canada have signed a
maritime agreement facilitating ship traffic between the two
countries, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The accord, Canada's first maritime pact with a foreign
country, was reached last week in Vancouver by visiting Chinese
Minister of Communications Huang Zhendong and Canadian Transport
Minister David Anderson, the newspaper cited information from the
Ministry of Communications (MOC) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The pact provides most-favored-nation (MFN) treatment
concerning port access and the assessment of port charges,
facilitates the opening of shipping-line offices, gives companies
tax relief and calls for closer cooperation in the investigation
of marine accidents.
</P>
<P>
Sources from MOC said that the accord followed another new
maritime agreement signed late last month between China and Israel
when Huang's delegation was visiting the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
According to the same sources, China has signed more than 50
bilateral maritime accords with other countries.
</P>
<P>
Gao Weijie, president of the Transport Department of the
Chinese Overseas Shipping Company (COSCO), said the new accord
will strengthen shipping links between COSCO and Canada and
increase the company's business there.
</P>
<P>
As a leading container shipping line in China, COSCO ranks
among the world's top five container services. The company's
vessels regularly sail directly to Canada's west coast port,
Vancouver, and to eastern Canada via New York Port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Assured of Sufficient Production Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 9 (Xinhua) -- The supply of agricultural
production materials will meet farmers' demands in this spring
sowing season, and their quality is ensured, today's China Daily
quoted a survey by the State Statistics Bureau as saying.
</P>
<P>
The supply of 13 surveyed materials, including fertilizers,
pesticides, and plastic sheeting, will cover more than 90 percent
of the demand and in some cases more than 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels spare no efforts to make those
materials available for farmers in order to further promote
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
In most province-level areas, there is an abundant or even
surplus of fertilizers, while in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, the supply is 77 percent more than demand.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that most areas have prepared abundant
farm-use tools, fuel and seeds.
</P>
<P>
Farm production means companies pledged to provide high quality
materials. A state company in Dingnan County, east China's Jianxi
Province, even told farmers that it would give awards to those who
turned out to buy fake or shoddy goods from any of its 68 supply
centres. 
</P>
</TEXT>
