<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Sleaze MP Confirmed as Conservative Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The local members of Britain's
ruling Conservative Party today confirmed Neil Hamilton, a
Conservative MP accused of taking cash for asking parliamentary
questions, as their candidate for the May 1 election.
</P>
<P>
Local Conservative Party Tresurer Tony Martin said Hamilton was
adopted by a vote of 182-100 by party members at a meeting in
Knutsford city in northwestern England, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Hamilton, former Conservative industry minister, has
consistently denied the allegations in the cash-for-questions
scandal that has forced another Conservative MP to step down. He
has resisted strong pressure from the Conservative party to quit
the election.
</P>
<P>
The Conservative Party has been hit hard by financial and
sexual scandals that had make it 20 points behind Labor Party in
opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
Hamilton's persistence to give way was challenged by BBC war
correspondent Martin Bell who stood last Sunday against him as an
anti-corruption candidate. He is supported by both main opposition
parties, the Labor and the Liberal Democrats, who have withdrawn
their candidates to boost Bell's bid.
</P>
<P>
Although many Conservative MP demanded Hamilton to step down,
Prime Minister John Major had refused to get involved, saying the
decision on who should stand for the seat of Tatton constituency
should be left to the local party.
</P>
<P>
"It is the responsibility of the people who elect their MP in
the Conservative Party to select or deselect a candidate, and it
is the responsibility of the candidate to decide whether or not
they will stand," Major told local press earlier today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
