<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House to Apologize for Syphilis Experiment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government will
formally apologize to the black men in Tuskegee, Alabama, whose
syphilis went untreated as part of a 40-year federal study, the
White House said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton will issue the apology soon, said White
House spokeswoman Mary Ellen Glynn.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced as four survivors of the experiments
came forward in Alabama to demand an apology.
</P>
<P>
The government has moved toward an apology for the Tuskegee
experiment in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
In the experiment, the U.S. Public Health Service withheld
treatment from 399 men between 1932 and 1972 to study how syphilis
spread and how it killed.
</P>
<P>
The men were not told they had the disease and were not given
penicillin, the standard treatment since 1947.
</P>
<P>
There are eight surviving participants, the youngest being 87
years old. Four of them met Tuesday at a church in Notasulga,
Alabama, that once served as an intake station for the study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
