<HEADLINE> UN Council Forwards to Assembly Judge Candidates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council today
forwarded to the General Assembly the nominations of 19 candidates
for Judges of the International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
With a resolution adopted unanimously, the council acted on the
nominations put forward by Secretary-General Kofi Annan on March
13 and forwarded the candidates to the Assembly, which will elect
11 as tribunal judges.
</P>
<P>
The council also adopted the Statute of the Tribunal and
decided that all states must cooperate fully with the tribunal and
take any measures necessary under their domestic law to implement
its Statute. The tribunal, established by Security Council
resolution 827 (1993), was inaugurated on 17 November 1993 at the
Peace Palace in the Hague. All the judges serve a four-year term.
</P>
<P>
According to its statute, the 11 judges of the tribunal shall
be elected by the General Assembly from a list submitted by the
Council. Candidates receiving an absolute majority in the Assembly
shall be declared elected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
