<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Senate to Vote on Chemical Weapons Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Republicans
today agreed to hold a ratification vote on the Chemical Weapons
Convention (CWC) before April 29, when the treaty goes into
effect.
</P>
<P>
Senate Republicans and Democratic leaders separately announced
the decision for a vote on the treaty, however without giving a
exact date. The ratification will need a two thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached while the Republicans attacked the
treaty during a Senate Foreign Relations Committee hearing.
</P>
<P>
Testifying before the hearing, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright appealed to the Committee late today for help
in ratifying the treaty, which she said is "one of the president's
top foreign policy priorities."
</P>
<P>
The CWC needs to pass the Committee before going to the full
Senate for ratification.
</P>
<P>
Opening the hearing on the convention, Jesse Helms, chairman of
the Committee, enlisted four former defense chiefs who spoke
against the treaty to block ratification of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Three former defense secretaries, James Schlesinger, Donald
Rumsfeld and Caspar Weinberger attended the hearing while Richard
Cheney, defense secretary under President George Bush sent a
letter to the hearing to criticize the CWC.
</P>
<P>
"The case against the treaty can be summarized quite simply, I
think. It is not global, it is not verifiable, it is not
constitutional, and it will not work," Helms told the hearing.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, signed in January, 1993 in paris, has been signed
by 161 countries and ratified by 70 of them up to now. It goes
into force on April 29.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration organized a rally last week,
attended by senior officials and arms experts, urging the Senate
to approve the treaty, which bans the development, production,
stockpiling, transfer and use of all chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton have recruited a long list of
prominent figures supporting the endorsement of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Supporters led by Clinton for the ratification of the treaty
argued that the treaty serves the interests of the U.S. and if it
is not ratified by the Senate before April 29, the U.S. will be in
the "company of the rogue states."
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the U.S. chemical companys will be restricted in
trade, resulting in a loss of millions of dollars for the U.S.
while the U.S. would lose its role in implementing the treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Envoy Calls for End of Nuclear Deterrence Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador for
Disarmament Affairs Sha Zukang on Tuesday called for an end of the
nuclear deterrence policy, which is exercised by the United
States, Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
He made the call in a speech to the First Session of the
Preparatory Committee for the 2000 Review Conference of the
Parties to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons
(NPT).
</P>
<P>
"It will be fair to say that since the indefinite extension of
the NPT in 1995, significant progress has been achieved in the
field of international arms control and disarmament," he said,
citing the adoption of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban (CTBT),
the coming into force of the Chemical Weapons Convention, etc.
</P>
<P>
But he said these developments are far from meeting the
expectations of the international community.
</P>
<P>
"some countries are still adhering to the policy of nuclear
deterrence based on the first use of nuclear weapons, and are
trying to find all excuses to justify their development and
deployment of missile defense systems which undermine strategic
security and stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China stands for the complete prohibition and
thorough destruction of nuclear weapons and regards NPT and CTBT
as intermediate steps leading to the complete prohibition and
thorough destruction of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
"Pending the complete elimination of nuclear weapons, the
nuclear-weapon states concerned should abandon their policy of
nuclear deterrence; states with the largest nuclear arsenals
should further reduce drastically their nuclear stockpiles;..." he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
