<HEADLINE> UN Commission on Sustainable Development Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Commission on
Sustainable Development must propose clear goals and targets
within the agreed framework of the 1992 United Nations Conference
on Environment and Development (UNCED), Mostafa Tolba of Egypt,
newly elected chairman of the commission, said at the opening of
its fifth session.
</P>
<P>
The commission should also raise specific recommendations to
the General Assembly's special session to review the Rio outcome
next June, he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted the current session would be different from previous
sessions since the Commission had a mandate to assess and review
everything that had and had not been achieved in the context of
the outcome of the Rio.
</P>
<P>
Joke Waller-Hunter, Director of the UN Division for Sustainable
Development, stressed that the commission should send a document
to the special session that provided solutions.
</P>
<P>
The document would be an input to the special session which
must convey a sense of urgency and reaffirm the highest-level
political support for sustainable development, recognizing the
interdependence of its economic, social and environmental
components, she added.
</P>
<P>
Chiefs of other UN agencies and representatives of several
countries also spoke at today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the three-week session, the 53-member commission would
function as a preparatory and negotiating body the for Assembly's
19th special session to be held in New York from June 23 to 27.
The special session will review the implementation of Agenda 21,
the program of action adopted by the UNCED in 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
