<HEADLINE> Home Prices in US Rising in Most Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The home prices in the U.S.,
Americans' most important assets, rose in most areas last year,
the U.S. National Association of Home Builders reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the median price of new and existing homes advanced
by 2.6 percent over the year to 120,000 dollars in the fourth
quarter, according to a survey released by the association.
</P>
<P>
That means home values, in general, rose with inflation. The
core inflation rate last year -- minus volatile food and energy
prices -- also was 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, 130 of 184 metro areas in the U.S. recorded median
price increases, while 39 showed a drop. There was no change in
nine areas, while comparative data were not available in six.
</P>
<P>
As usual, the highest median prices of homes were mostly in
California while the lowest median prices were in some areas of
New York, Iowa and Ohio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
