<HEADLINE> Dollar Rallies Further, Surpasses 126 yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar shot past 126 yen
for the first time in more than 4 years Tuesday after Japan's
trade minister indicated he wasn't too concerned about the U.S.
currency's vitality.
</P>
<P>
The dollar hit an intraday high of 126.52 yen, the strongest
since August 1992, before settling in New York at 126.23 yen, up
from 125.56 yen Monday. The dollar cost 1.7143 marks, up from
1.7109 and the highest since March 6. The pound cost 1.6260 U.S.
dollars, down from 1.6295 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The remarks by Shinji Sato came one day after the dollar
surpassed 125 yen for the first time since January 1993, and were
interpreted by traders as a signal that both Japan and the United
States won't intervene to halt the U.S. currency's ascent
currently.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was helped by the third straight day of gains
in the U.S. stock market as well as a continuous weakness in the
mark, which suffered from growing expectations that Europe's
single currency will be launched as scheduled as well as news that
German employment remained inactive in March.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Monday: 1.4735
Swiss francs, up from 1.4674; 5.7660 French francs, up from 5.7530;
1,688.50 Italian lira, up from 1,684.00; 1.3882 Canadian dollars,
up from 1.3867.  
</P>
</TEXT>
