<HEADLINE> France, Russia to Coordinate Action over Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- France and Russia will coordinate
their actions over the Middle East to help end the impasse of the
peace process for the region, said French Foreign Minister Herve
de Charette and his Russian counterpart Yevgeni Primakov today.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to work together, in a coordinated way, to give
a strong impulse to the peace process," said Primakov after
having a two-hour meeting with de Charette.
</P>
<P>
Primakov arrived here this afternoon to discuss with French
leaders the relations between Russia and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"We shared an extreme worry over the situation concerning the
Middle East and the peace process," said de Charette. "We agreed
to keep in close touch to put together our efforts, between Russia
for one side, and France and Europe for the other, in order to
renew the thread of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that the peace process cannot be resumed
unless on the basis of the agreements already signed by Israel and
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process has entered an impasse after
Israel decided to build a new housing project in Har Homa district
of East Jerusalem, which triggered a wave of angry protests from
the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
