<HEADLINE> Recruitment Picks up in UK Financial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Employment in Britain's financial
service sector rose for the first time in the past three months in
more than two years, according to the latest survey of the sector
by the Confederation of British Industry (CBI) and Coopers &AMP;
Lybrand, the consultants.
</P>
<P>
The survey, published Monday and covering more than 300
companies, showed that a positive balance of 11 percent of firms
reported staff recruitment, compared with negative balances of
nine percent in December and 29 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The report said that stockbrokers and fund managers led the way
in boosting employment while general insurers and insurance
brokers continued to cut staff heavily.
</P>
<P>
But the rise in employment is likely to level off during the
next three months, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Although the CBI said that the figures were encouraging, it
pointed out that "the survey does indicate a reduced tempo of
growth" as demand was expected to rise only slightly over the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
Overall business optimism rose for the fifth quarter in a row,
but the pick-up was slower than at any time since December 1995,
with the positive balance down from 61 percent to 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
Growth in business volumes also slowed from a positive balance
of 79 percent in the December survey to 39 percent, with
securities traders, banks and venture capitalists reporting the
largest increases in volumes while building societies reporting a
small decrease.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that the sector's spending on information
technology will continue to be strong while investment in land and
buildings is expected to fall.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
