<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Questions Remain Between Russia, NATO: Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni
Primakov said here today that "many questions remain to be
solved" before Russia and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) can reach an agreement defining the relations between the
two former enemies during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
During his meetings with French Foreign Minister Herve de
Charette and Prime Minister Alain Juppe, Primakov renewed Russia's
opposition to the eastward expansion plan by NATO, which Moscow
regards as a threat for its national security, reported Agence
France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
He said that although Russia is working hard to "obtain a
document" with NATO, this does not mean that it has changed its
attitude toward the expansion of the Western military alliance,
but is only an attempt by Moscow to "minimize the consequences
which could result from the enlargement of NATO."
</P>
<P>
Primakov refused to say in which date or venue Russia will sign
such a document with NATO, and only said that Moscow wishes to
conclude the agreement "as rapidly as possible."
</P>
<P>
He said that he discussed with French foreign minister Russia's
concern over "the perspective of the advancement of the military
infrastructure of NATO toward the frontiers of Russia."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the wish that a treaty on the reduction of
conventional arms in Europe be modernized, and recalled that
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill Clinton
agreed in Helsinki last month to accelerate negotiations on
reduction of conventional weapons in Europe in order to attain an
agreement by the Summer of this year.
</P>
<P>
"Up to now we (Russia and the United States) have agreed to
avoid the deployment of combat forces of NATO in a permanent way
beyond the territories of the 16 (NATO) member countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Although NATO has agreed that it will not deploy nuclear
weapons or permanently deploy troops in the countries to be
absorbed by it, it has never promised Moscow that it will never
deploy military infrastructure in these countries.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic will be absorbed by NATO
in the first wave of its expansion in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970409.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-08 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
