<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's GDP Growth Should Be in 9-10% Range in 1997, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Assuming a strong global economy,
China's GDP growth should be in the 9-10% range in 1997, according
to HSBC's monthly report, "Global Outlook", published here today.
</P>
<P>
The report said, China achieved its goal of a soft landing for
the economy in 1996 as GDP growth eased to 9.7% from 10.5% in
1995.
</P>
<P>
After rising by 13.1% in 1996 and 13.7% in Q4 alone, its
industrial output (value-added) growth fell to 10.3% in January.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales of consumer goods in China, however, have remained
buoyant, increasing by 16% in January, up from 13.5% in Q4.
</P>
<P>
Global Outlook said, China's retail inflation was at 3.3% in
January, compared with 4.6% in Q4 and an average of 6.1% for all
of 1996. January's consumer price inflation was 5.9% versus 6.8%
in Q4.
</P>
<P>
Inflation should remain at the single digit level in 1997 due
to measures such as China's continued tight credit policy, it
added.
</P>
<P>
China's exports continued its recovery in the second half,
cumulating in a rise of 12.2% in Q4. Imports recorded positive
growth of 3.6% Q4 and 12.2 Billion US dollars for 1996.
</P>
<P>
China's trade surplus expanded further by 1.7 billion US
dollars in January, with exports rising by 27.5% and imports
declining by 1.2% during the month.
</P>
<P>
The poor import performance in January, the report said,
indicated that the rebound in late 1996 was probably due to a rush
by certain foreign-invested enterprises to break the end-1996
deadline for the elimination of tax/duty exemptions on capital
goods imports.
</P>
<P>
Utilized foreign direct investment (FDI) in China maintained
steady growth, rising by 8.5% in Q4 following growth of 7.7% in
Q3, according to HSBC.
</P>
<P>
Contractual FDI in China, however, continued to fall, down by
62.6% in Q4 after a decline of 32% in Q3 that was due mainly to
the withdrawal of import tax and duty exemptions for foreign
investors on 1 April 1996.
</P>
<P>
An expanding trade surplus and steady capital inflow boosted
foreign exchange reserves in China to the record level of 105
billion US dollars by end-1996, up from 73.6 billion US dollars at
end-1995.
</P>
<P>
The Renminbi exchange rate against the US dollar remained
within the 8.30-8.33 range throughout 1996, but the unit has been
trading on the strong side since last July, rising to 8.29 by the
end of February 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a major move to reform its foreign exchange regime, China
declared the Renminbi fully convertible for current account
transactions in line with International Monetary Fund requirements
starting 1st December, four years ahead of the original schedule.
</P>
<P>
So far, the new arrangement has not had any noticeable impact
on the Renminbi exchange rate, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
