<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Car Exports to U.S. Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese car makers are
increasing their sales in the United States, taking the advantage
of a soft yen.
</P>
<P>
The major three automakers in the U.S. said Japanese companies
are playing the weak yen and exports to boost profits and Japan's
weak economy.
</P>
<P>
The complaints come as Japan's trade surplus with the U.S.
widened in February for the second month in a row. Autos and auto
parts account for two-thirds of the surplus.
</P>
<P>
In New York trading today, the U.S. dollar hit an intraday high
of 126.52 yen, the strongest since August 1992, before settling at
126.23 yen, up from 125.56 yen Monday. The dollar-has jumped 57
percent against the yen during the past two years and is up 9
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The weak yen has helped Japanese automakers widen their
profits. In January, vehicles exported from Japan to the United
States leaped 75 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported that Japanese automakers have gained about
2 percentage points of the market share in the U.S. this year. And
U.S. automakers have lost about 2.5 points.
</P>
<P>
But Japanese automakers argued that it was market demand that
fueled the increases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
