<HEADLINE> President Mobutu Declares State of Emergency in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Ailing President Mobutu Sese Seko
declared a state of emergency today in Zaire, the third largest
country in Africa, about a third of which is under rebel control,
a report from Kinshasa said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking over state television in the Zairean capital, Mobutu
said a state of emergency declared in the eastern provinces of
north and south Kivu last year "is extended throughout the
national territory".
</P>
<P>
Five military governors had been appointed in provinces not
held by the rebels, said Mobutu, who added the emergency covers
capital Kinshasa which has five million people.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu, who seized power in 1965, has seen his hold over the
country weakened by relentless rebel advances. The rebel Alliance
of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL)
took up arms last October vowing to topple him.
</P>
<P>
They took Kisangani, the third largest city in Zaire in late
March after foiling an offensive launched by government troops in
February. Their forces are now advancing toward Lubumbashi,
capital of copper-rich Shaba province and they have vowed to
seize Kinshasa in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
