<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuel Scarcity to Ebb in Lagos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Lingering fuel scarcity in Lagos
may soon ebb, as the head of state General Sani Abacha has
ordered immediate supply of fuel to the largest Nigerian city.
</P>
<P>
Military Administrator of Lagos State Mohammed Marwa announced
this to anxious motorists outside a petrol station in Lagos
today.
</P>
<P>
He told the people that the head of state has ordered the
importation of more fuel to end the crisis that started about
three weeks ago in Lagos and has spread to other parts of the
country, including Abuja, the national capital.
</P>
<P>
The head of state is especially concerned about Lagos because
it is the economic nerve center of the country, he said, adding
that the fuel scarcity would be over in a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Lagos have been much limited in their movement in
the past days. Fuel scarcity has also driven bus fares and food
prices higher.
</P>
<P>
Worried by spreading fuel crisis, Abacha called the
administrators and oil industry officials to the capital on
Monday to find a solution.
</P>
<P>
According to Marwa, the government will also move to repair
the country's ailing refineries, which are the fundamental reason
behind the outbreak of fuel crisis from time to time in this
largest oil producing country in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
